{"title_page": "Ichthyovenator", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Aptian]]) {{fossilrange|125|113}}\n| image = Ichthyovenator laosensis.jpg\n| image_caption = Casts of the known [[spinal column]] at the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo. The thirteenth [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] spine and the lower part of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacrum]] have been partially reconstructed.\n| image_alt = White casts of fossil spinal column with a wave-like sail on display at a museum\n| taxon = Ichthyovenator\n| authority = Allain ''et al.'', [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Ichthyovenator laosensis'''''\n| type_species_authority = Allain ''et al.'', 2012\n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = \n}}\n\n'''''Ichthyovenator''''' is a [[genus]] of [[spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived in what is now Laos during the [[Aptian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]], sometime between 125 to 113 million years ago. It is known from [[Fossil|fossils]] collected in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]], the first of which were found in 2010, and comprised a partial skeleton without the skull or limbs. This specimen became the [[holotype]] of the new genus and [[species]] '''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''', and was described by [[palaeontologist]] Ronan Allain and colleagues in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]. The generic name, meaning \"fish hunter\", refers to its assumed [[piscivorous]] lifestyle, while the specific name alludes to the country of Laos. In 2014, it was announced that further remains from the dig site had been recovered; these fossils included teeth as well as more [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#vertebrae|vertebrae]] (backbones) and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubic bone]] from the same individual.\n\nThe holotype specimen is estimated to have been between {{convert|8.5 to 10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long and weighed {{convert|2 to 2.4|t|short ton|abbr=}}. ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s teeth were straight and conical, and its neck resembled that of the closely related ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''. Like others in its family, ''Ichthyovenator'' had tall [[neural spines]] forming a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back. Unlike other known spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail had a [[sinusoidal]] (wave-like) shape, curving downwards over the hips into two separate sails. The [[pelvic girdle]] was reduced, with the length ratio between the main body of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] and the pubes and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischium|ischia]] being higher than in any other known theropod dinosaurs. The animal was initially thought to belong to the [[Baryonychinae]] [[subfamily]], but more recent analyses place it as a primitive member in the [[Spinosaurinae]].\n\nAs a spinosaur, ''Ichthyovenator'' would have had a long, shallow snout and robust forelimbs. Its diet likely consisted mainly of aquatic prey (hence its etymology). Spinosaurids are also known to have eaten small dinosaurs and [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] in addition to fish. ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s conspicuous sail might have been used for [[sexual display]] or [[species recognition]]. Fossil evidence suggests that spinosaurids, especially spinosaurines, were adapted for [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. The vertebral spines of ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s tail were unusually tall, suggesting that\u2014as in today's [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]\u2014the tail may have aided in swimming. ''Ichthyovenator'' lived alongside [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as [[Bivalvia|bivalves]], fish and turtles.\n\n==Discovery and naming==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_skeletal_%26_size_comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|left|alt=Drawing of fossil rib, backbones and pelvis superimposed on silhouette of a dinosaur|Skeletal diagram with [[holotype]] elements in place, excluding the additional [[fossil]] material announced in 2014]]\n\nThe first [[fossil|fossils]] of ''Ichthyovenator'' were found in 2010 at [[Ban Kalum]], in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]] in [[Savannakhet Province]], Laos. These bones were recovered from a [[red sandstone]] layer, within a surface area of less than {{convert|2|m|ftin|sp=|abbr=}} squared. Designated under the specimen numbers MDS BK10-01 to 15, it consists of a partly [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#articulation|articulated]], well preserved skeleton lacking the skull and limbs, and including the third to last [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] (back) [[vertebra]], the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#neural spine|neural spine]] of the last dorsal vertebra, five partial [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacral]] (hip) vertebrae, the first two [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae, both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ilium|ilia]] (main hip bone), a right [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubis]] (pubic bone), both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischium|ischia]] (lower and rearmost hip bones) and a posterior dorsal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ribs|rib]]. The twelfth dorsal spine is bent sideways when viewed front-to-back due to [[Taphonomy|taphonomic]] distorsion, and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#centrum|centra]] (bodies of the vertebrae) of the sacrals are largely incomplete due to erosion, but preserved all their accompanying spines with their upper edges intact. At the time of ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description, excavations at the site were still ongoing.<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref>\n\nAfter undergoing preparation in 2011, the skeleton was used as the basis, or [[holotype]], for the [[type species]] ''Ichthyovenator laosensis''; named and described in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]] by [[palaeontologist|palaeontologists]] Ronan Allain, Tiengkham Xeisanavong, Philippe Richir, and Bounsou Khentavong. The [[Generic name (biology)|generic name]] is derived from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f30\u03c7\u03b8\u03cd\u03c2 (''ichthys''), \"fish\", and [[Latin]] ''venator'', \"hunter\", in reference to its likely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] refers to its provenance from Laos.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> ''Ichthyovenator'' is the third named [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] from Asia, after the Thai genus ''[[Siamosaurus]]'' in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], and the Chinese species \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' in [[2009 in archosaur paleontology|2009]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref>Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref><ref name=\"EBetal08\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B}}</ref> The latter may represent the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892|via=}}</ref>''\n\nIn 2014, a [[Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|''Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology'']] abstract on the genus was published by Allain. This abstract indicated that additional remains from the original individual had been found after an excavation in 2012. These remains include three teeth, the left pubis, and many vertebrae, including a nearly complete neck, the first dorsal vertebra, and seven more caudal vertebrae. However, this abstract has not been formally published as an academic paper as of 2020.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Some of these additional vertebrae were compared with those of other spinosaurids in a 2015 paper by German palaeontologist Serjoscha Evers and colleagues, in which they noted multiple similarities with the vertebrae of the African spinosaurid ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Evers|first=Serjoscha W.|last2=Rauhut|first2=Oliver W.M.|last3=Milner|first3=Angela C.|last4=McFeeters|first4=Bradley|last5=Allain|first5=Ronan|date=2015|title=A reappraisal of the morphology and systematic position of the theropod dinosaur Sigilmassasaurus from the \"middle\" Cretaceous of Morocco|url=|journal=PeerJ|language=en|volume=3|pages=e1323|doi=10.7717/peerj.1323|issn=2167-8359|pmc=4614847|pmid=26500829}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Spinosauridae_Size_Diagram_by_PaleoGeek_-_Version_2.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Silhouettes of five left-facing spinosaurid dinosaurs compared with a blue human to their left, Ichthyovenator in yellow, second from right|Size of various [[spinosaurid]]s (''Ichthyovenator'' in yellow, second from right) compared with a human|alt=]]\n\nIn 2016, American palaeontologist [[Gregory S. Paul]] estimated ''Ichthyovenator'' to have been approximately {{convert|8.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long and to have weighed {{convert|2|t|short ton|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=S.|first=Paul, Gregory|title=The Princeton field guide to dinosaurs|date=2016|publisher=|isbn=9781400883141|edition=2nd|location=Princeton, N.J.|pages=|oclc=954055249}}</ref> The same year, Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi gave a higher estimate of {{convert|10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=on}} in length, {{convert|2.95|m|ftin|sp=|abbr=on}} tall at the hips, and {{convert|2.4|t|short ton|abbr=on}} in weight.<ref>{{Cite book|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|last=Molina-P\u00e9rez & Larramendi|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=259}}</ref>\n\n''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s teeth were conical, straight, and bore no [[Serration|serrations]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The front carinae (edges) of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#maxilla|maxillary]] and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentary|dentary]] teeth were evident on the base of the [[tooth crown]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The front articulating surfaces of ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s rear cervical and front dorsal vertebrae were one and a half times wider than they were high and wider than the length of their centra. They also bore robust front [[Tubercle (bone)|tubercles]] ([[Process (anatomy)|processes]] for [[skeletal muscle]] attachment) and lacked inter[[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#zygapophyseal laminae|zygapophyseal laminae]], which resulted in their spinopre- and spinopostzygapophyseal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#fossae|fossae]] (depressions) having open undersides. The first dorsal vertebra had extensive [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#transverse processes|transverse processes]] (wing-like projections that articulate with the ribs), as well as deep air pockets at the front and back of its base. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#parapophyses|parapophysis]] (a process that articulated with the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#capitulum|capitulum]] of the ribs) of the first dorsal increased in height, with its underside remaining in contact with the front lower edge of the centrum. This is unlike the condition in most theropods, where the parapophyses shifted towards the top of the vertebra during the transition from cervical to dorsal vertebrae. All of these features were also present in ''Sigilmassasaurus''. ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s mid-cervical vertebrae all had elongate, somewhat wider than tall centra that became progressively shorter towards the rear of the neck, as well as well-developed keels on their bottom surfaces, traits all shared with the spinosaurids ''[[Baryonyx]], [[Suchomimus]]'', ''Sigilmassasaurus'',<ref name=\":1\" /> and ''[[Vallibonavenatrix]]''.<ref name=\":3\">Elisabete Malafaia; Jos\u00e9 Miguel Gasulla; Fernando Escaso; Iv\u00e1n Narv\u00e1ez; Jos\u00e9 Luis Sanz; Francisco Ortega (2019). \"A new spinosaurid theropod (Dinosauria: Megalosauroidea) from the late Barremian of Vallibona, Spain: Implications for spinosaurid diversity in the Early Cretaceous of the Iberian Peninsula\". Cretaceous Research. in press: 104221. {{doi|10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104221}}.</ref> The cervical neural spines of ''Ichthyovenator'' were taller than in ''Sigilmassasaurus'' and ''Baryonyx'', but shared the blade-like shape with those two taxa at the mid-cervicals.<ref name=\":1\" /> The single known dorsal rib, which was found near the twelfth dorsal vertebra, had a head typical of the ribs of other moderately to large-sized theropods. The rib shaft was strongly curved, forming a half circle. The lower end of the rib was slightly expanded both sideways and to the front and back. This condition, which differs from the tapered, pointed tips seen in the ribs of other known theropods, suggests that the rearmost dorsal ribs articulated with the complex of the [[sternum]] (breast bone).<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_65849.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Cast fossil spinal column laid out inside a glass display case at a museum|Casts of the [[Vertebra|vertebrae]] at the [[Mus\u00e9um national d'histoire naturelle|Mus\u00e9um National d'Histoire Naturelle]], Paris|alt=|left]]\n\nLike many other spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator'' had a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back and hips, formed by the elongated [[neural spines]] of its vertebrae. Uniquely among known members of the family however, ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s sail was divided in two over the hip, and had a [[sinusoid]] (wave-like) curvature. This is in contrast to the related genera ''[[Spinosaurus]]'' and ''Suchomimus'' (both of which had continuous sails that rose to a peak before sloping down again), and B''aryonyx'' (which showed a less developed sail, having much lower dorsal spines). ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s preserved dorsal and sacral [[spinal column]], over {{Convert|1|m||abbr=on}} long, shows a very high spine on the twelfth dorsal vertebra, representing a crest that rose from the back, and a lower rounded sail that extended from the sacral vertebrae of the hips, with its highest point above the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|54.6|cm||adj=on}} high spine of the twelfth dorsal vertebra widened towards the top, giving it a [[Trapezoid|trapezoidal]] shape, whereas the spines of other spinosaurids were roughly rectangular. It also lacked the forward or backward inclination of ''Spinosaurus''{{'}}s neural spines. Its front corner formed a {{Convert|3|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} narrow process, pointing upwards. The spine of the thirteenth dorsal vertebra has only been partly preserved, its upper and lower ends having broken off. From its general shape the describers inferred however, that it was about as long as the preceding spine. This would imply that the back edge of the front sail would form a rectangular corner, as the spine of the much lower first sacral vertebra is about {{Convert|21|cm||abbr=on}}, creating a sudden hiatus in the profile of the sail. The spine of the second sacral vertebra steeply curved upwards again, joining the {{Convert|39|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|48|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} high broad fan-shaped spines of the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|40|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} tall spine of the fifth sacral gradually descended. Unlike in most other theropods, including the sail of ''Suchomimus'', the sacral spines were not fused, nor did they have any extensive contacts. The second and third sacral centra were [[co-ossified]] (fused), with the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]] connecting them still visible. Since only the rearmost two dorsal vertebrae are preserved, it is unknown how far the dorsal sail continued towards the front of the animal's back.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour life reconstruction of a left-facing spinosaur|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]], with unknown regions such as the head and limbs based on relatives]]\n\nThe sacral sail was continued by the spines of the first two caudal vertebrae, which were {{Convert|28.4|cm||adj=|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|25.7|cm||adj=|abbr=on}} tall respectively. They leaned backwards at a 30 degree angle, and had smooth front and rear edges. The centra of the first two caudals were much broader than long and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#amphicoelous|amphicoelous]] (deeply concave on both ends). The caudal transverse processes were prominent, sturdy, and angled upwards towards the rear of the vertebrae. The transverse processes of the first caudal vertebra, when seen from above, had a [[Sigmoid function|sigmoid]] (or S-shaped) profile. The prespinal and postspinal fossae (bony depressions in front and behind the neural spines) were confined to above the base of the neural spines. The sides of the first caudal were also deeply hollowed out between the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#Prezygapophyses|prezygapophyses]] (articular surfaces with the neural arch of the preceding vertebra) and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#diapophyses|diapophyses]] (processes on the sides for rib articulation), a condition not observed in other theropods.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Some of the caudal vertebrae also had unusually tall, forwardly-extended prezygapophyses.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe {{Convert|92|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} ilium of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] was blade-like, and longer in proportion to the pubic bone, which was {{Convert|65|cm||adj=|abbr=on}} long, than in any other known large theropod. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#postacetabular process|postacetabular ala]] (front expansion) was much longer than the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#preacetabular process|preacetabular ala]] (rear expansion), the latter had a shelf on its central surface, which formed the middle edge of the preacetabular fossa. Viewed distally (from away from the centre of attachment), the lower end of the pubis was L-shaped, resembling that of ''Baryonyx''. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic apron|pubic apron]] (the expanded lower end of the pubis) features a large [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic foramen|pubic foramen]]. On the hind rim of the pubic bone, two openings, the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#obturator%20foramen|obturator foramen]] and a lower [[fenestra]] (opening), were not fully closed, making them into notches. The ischium was {{Convert|49.6|cm|in|adj=|abbr=on}} long, making it shorter in relation to the pubis than in all other known [[Tetanurae|tetanuran]] theropods. Its main body was large and extensive, atypical of the Y-shaped upper ischia of other tetanurans, and bore an oval-shaped obturator foramen in its side. The shaft of the ischium was flattened sideways, and had an unexpanded [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischiadic apron|ischiadic apron]] (as in ''[[Monolophosaurus]]'' and ''[[Sinraptor]]'').<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> The ischium attached to the illium via a peg-and-socket-like articulation, unlike the flat and concave condition seen in ''Baryonyx''. This feature was also present in ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:20130825_Brazil_Rio_de_Janeiro_0144.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Reconstructed skeleton of a spinosaurid holding a pterosaur skeleton in its jaws against a painted backdrop|Reconstructed skeleton of the [[spinosaurine]] ''[[Irritator]]'', mounted at the [[National Museum of Rio de Janeiro]]]]\n\nAllain and his team considered ''Ichthyovenator'' as representing the first unequivocal spinosaurid from Asia.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Though prior spinosaurids had been named from the continent; including ''Siamosaurus'' from the [[Barremian]] [[Sao Khua Formation]] of Thailand, and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' from the [[Aptian]] [[Xinlong Formation]] of China, the authors noted that the validity of these taxa has been debated by palaeontologists, due to them only being confidently known from isolated teeth.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\" /> In 2017, Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Caesar Schultz suggested that these teeth may eventually be attributed to spinosaurids similar to ''Ichthyovenator''.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966}}</ref> However, American researcher Mickey Mortimer pointed out that a spinosaurid skeleton, possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus'', was excavated from the Thai [[Khok Kruat Formation]] in 2004,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and identified as a definite spinosaur in a 2008 conference abstract by British palaeontologist [[Angela Milner]] and colleagues.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> Mortimer stated that even if teeth are ruled out, confirmed evidence of spinosaurids in Asia was known eight years before ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2012, ''Ichthyovenator'' was assigned by Allain and colleagues to the Spinosauridae, more precisely to the subfamily [[Baryonychinae]] in a [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] position as the [[sister species]] of a [[clade]] formed by ''Baryonyx'' and ''Suchomimus''. The describers established the following [[autapomorphies]] (unique derived traits) in ''Ichthyovenator'': its dorsal and sacral sinusoidal sail; the thirteenth dorsal neural spine being 410% the length of the centrum, and having a distinct finger-shaped process on its front upper corner; the broad, expanded tips of the third and fourth sacral spines; the first caudal vertebra's deep prezygapophyseal centrodiapophyseal fossae and S-shaped transverse processes in top view; and the lengthy illium, with its accompanying pubis being shorter in comparison to it than in any other known theropod. Allain and colleagues also identified some anatomical features unique among tetanuran theropods, including the rearmost dorsal ribs articulating with the sternal complex, the pubis's main body having obturator and pubic openings, and the ischium having a foramen on its upper end, as well as a shaft that was flatenned sideways. The shrinking of the pubis and ischium relative to the pelvis has been observed in basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaurs]] and [[Allosauroidea|allosauroids]], which the describers attributed to [[mosaic evolution]]: the evolution of certain anatomical traits at different times in separate species.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> \n\n[[File:Spinosauridae_\"Sails\"_Comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Three pairs of illustrated fossil pelvic bones and spinal columns compared to the silhouette of a human to their left, Ichthyovenator's pelvis and vertebrae first from the bottom|Comparison of the [[pelvic region]] and [[Neural spine sail|neural spine sails]] of ''[[Suchomimus]]'', ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', and ''Ichthyovenator'']]\n\nIn 2014, Allain's abstract instead found that ''Ichthyovenator'' was part of the subfamily [[Spinosaurinae]], due to the lack of serrations on its teeth and the possession of vertebrae with some similarities to those of ''Sigilmassasaurus''.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2015, a [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] analysis by Evers and colleagues suggested that given the apparent presence of both baryonychine and spinosaurine characteristics in ''Ichthyovenator'', the distinction between the two subfamilies may not be as clear as previously thought.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mortimer hypothesized in 2017 that ''Ichthyovenator'' may not have been a spinosaurid at all, instead possibly being a sail-backed [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] dinosaur closely related to ''[[Concavenator]]''. She thus placed ''Ichthyovenator'' as [[Incertae sedis|''incertae sedis'']] (of uncertain taxonomic affinity) within the clade [[Orionides]], pending description of the new material, which she states will likely confirm ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s spinosaurid identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Ichthyovenatorlaosensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=2017|website=The Theropod Database}}</ref> A 2017 analysis by Sales and Schultz questioned Baryonychinae's validity, citing the [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of Brazilian spinosaurids ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Angaturama'' as suggesting they were possible [[Transitional fossil|transitionary forms]] between the earlier baryonychines and the later spinosaurines. The authors thus indicated that with further research, Baryonychinae may turn out to be a [[paraphyletic]] (unnatural) grouping.<ref name=\":17\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s spinosaurine classification was supported by British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues in 2018, who resolved it as a basal member of the group due to its tall dorsal sail. Their [[cladogram]] can be seen below:<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2018|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1=''[[Siamosaurus suteethorni]]''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1='''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\n\n== Palaeobiology ==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator vertebrae.jpg|thumb|alt=White casts of spinal column with wave-like sail laid out on a dark background in a museum exhibit|Casts of the vertebrae seen from behind]]\n\nThough no skull remains have been found for ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had elongated, low and narrow snouts which allowed them to reach far for food and close their jaws quickly, akin to modern [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]. The tips of their upper and lower jaws fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape that bore long teeth, behind which there was a notch in the upper jaw; this formed a natural trap for prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s straight and unserrated teeth,<ref name=\":0\" /> like those of other spinosaurids, would have been suitable for impaling and capturing small animals and aquatic prey. This type of jaw and tooth morphology, also observed in today's [[gharials]] and other fish-eating predators, has led many palaeontologists to believe that spinosaurids were largely piscivorous (as implied in ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s name).<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cuff|first=Andrew R.|last2=Rayfield|first2=Emily J.|date=2013|title=Feeding Mechanics in Spinosaurid Theropods and Extant Crocodilians|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=8|issue=5|pages=e65295|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0065295|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3665537|pmid=23724135|bibcode=2013PLoSO...865295C}}</ref> This is also evidenced by ''[[Scheenstia]]'' fish scales discovered in the stomach cavity of one ''Baryonyx'' skeleton,<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=L\u00f3pez-Arbarello|first1=A.|year=2012|title=Phylogenetic Interrelationships of Ginglymodian Fishes (Actinopterygii: Neopterygii)|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=7|issue=7|pages=e39370|bibcode=2012PLoSO...739370L|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0039370|pmc=3394768|pmid=22808031}}</ref> and a ''Spinosaurus'' snout found with a vertebra from the [[sawfish]] ''[[Onchopristis]]'' embedded in it.<ref name=\"dalsassoetal05\">{{cite journal|last=dal Sasso|first=C.|author2=Maganuco, S.|author3=Buffetaut, E.|author4=Mendez, M.A.|year=2005|title=New information on the skull of the enigmatic theropod ''Spinosaurus'', with remarks on its sizes and affinities|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume=25|issue=4|pages=888\u2013896|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2005)025[0888:NIOTSO]2.0.CO;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> A more [[generalist diet]] for spinosaurs has also been proposed, based on fossils such as juvenile ''[[Iguanodon]]'' bones also found in the aforementioned ''Baryonyx'' specimen, and an ''Irritator'' tooth embedded in the vertebrae of a [[pterosaur]]. Thus, it is likely that spinosaurids were also scavengers and hunters of larger prey than fish.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"milner2007\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Andrew|last2=Kirkland|first2=James|date=September 2007|title=The case for fishing dinosaurs at the St. George Dinosaur Discovery Site at Johnson Farm|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285906225|journal=Utah Geological Survey Notes|volume=39|pages=1\u20133|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sales|first1=M. A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=M. B.|last3=Horn|first3=B. L. D.|last4=de Oliveira|first4=I. A. P.|last5=Schultz|first5=C. L.|last6=Bibi|first6=F.|date=2016|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmc=4734717|pmid=26829315|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref> Though no limb bones are known from ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had well-built arms with enlarged thumb claws, which they likely used to hunt and process prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> \n\n[[File:CrocoLoco-swimming-01.jpg|thumb|left|Three images of a crocodile in the water at different stages of swimming sequence as it propels itself with its tail|''Ichthyovenator'' might have used its tail, which had elongated neural spines, for propulsion through water, similar to [[crocodilians]] such as this [[Nile crocodile]]<ref name=\"arden2018\" />]]\n\nMany possible functions, including [[thermoregulation]] and energy storage, have been proposed for spinosaurid sails.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"JBB97\">{{cite journal|last=Bailey|first=J.B.|year=1997|title=Neural spine elongation in dinosaurs: sailbacks or buffalo-backs?|journal=Journal of Paleontology|volume=71|issue=6|pages=1124\u20131146|doi=10.1017/S0022336000036076|jstor=1306608}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues posited that given the high diversity in neural spine elongation observed in different theropod dinosaurs, as well as [[histological]] research done on the sails of [[Synapsid|synapsids]] (stem mammals), ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s sinusoidal sail may have instead been used for [[courtship display]] or for [[Species recognition|recognising members of its own species]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In a 2013 blog post, British palaeontologist [[Darren Naish]] considered the latter function unlikely, favouring the hypothesis of [[sexual selection]] for ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s sail, since it appears to have evolved on its own, without very close relatives. Naish also notes that it is possible that similar relatives have not been discovered yet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/tetrapod-zoology/species-recognition-vs-sexual-selection-in-dinosaurs/|title=Dinosaurs and their exaggerated structures : species recognition aids, or sexual display devices?|last=Naish|first=Darren|date=2013|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nSpinosaurids appear to have had [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles, spending much of their time near or in water, as has been inferred by the high density of their limb bones (which would have made them less [[Buoyancy|buoyant]]), and the [[Isotope ratio|isotope ratios]] of their teeth being closer to those of aquatic animals like turtles, crocodilians, and hippopotamuses than those of other, more terrestrial theropods.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Semiaquatic adaptations seem to have been more developed in spinosaurines than baryonychines.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /><ref name=\"Holtz 1998\">{{Cite journal|last1=Holtz Jr.|first1=T. R.|year=1998|title=Spinosaurs as crocodile mimics|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ac3ac036aeff2608055324d2f1186e8359059706|journal=Science|volume=282|issue=5392|pages=1276\u20131277|doi=10.1126/science.282.5392.1276}}</ref><ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=N.|last2=Sereno|first2=P. C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=C.|last4=Maganuco|first4=S.|last5=Fabri|first5=M.|last6=Martill|first6=D. M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=S.|last8=Myhrvold|first8=N.|last9=Lurino|first9=D. A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20131616|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref> ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s short pubis and ischium relative to its illium, coupled with the elongated neural spines in the tails of early spinosaurs, were suggested by Arden and colleagues in 2018 as indications that spinosaurids may have progressively employed further use of their tails to propel themselves underwater (similarly to crocodilians) as they grew more adapted towards an aquatic lifestyle.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /> A similar, though more extreme shrinkage of the pelvis and hind limbs was observed in ''Spinosaurus'', which appears to have been more semiaquatic than any other known spinosaur species.<ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_20142\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=Nizar|last2=Sereno|first2=Paul C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=Cristiano|last4=Maganuco|first4=Simone|last5=Fabri|first5=Matteo|last6=Martill|first6=David M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=Samir|last8=Myhrvold|first8=Nathan|last9=Lurino|first9=Dawid A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20136|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref>\n\n== Palaeoecology and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Caudal vertebrae Tangvayosaurus hoffeti.jpg|thumb|Fossils of the [[sauropod]] ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'', another dinosaur from the [[Gres superieurs Formation]], [[Savannakhet]] Dinosaur Museum]]\n\n''Ichthyovenator'' is known from the Barremian to [[Cenomanian]] Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation, and was found in a layer probably dating to the Aptian [[Stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], between 125 to 113 million years ago.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> It coexisted with other dinosaurs such as the [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'', and an indeterminate sauropod, [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]], and [[neoceratopsian]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Cavin|first=Lionel|last2=Deesri|first2=Uthumporn|last3=Veran|first3=Monette|last4=Khentavong|first4=Bounsou|last5=Jintasakul|first5=Pratueng|last6=Chanthasit|first6=Phornphen|last7=Allain|first7=Ronan|date=2019-03-04|title=A new Lepisosteiformes (Actinopterygii: Ginglymodi) from the Early Cretaceous of Laos and Thailand, SE Asia|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=17|issue=5|pages=393\u2013407|doi=10.1080/14772019.2018.1426060|issn=1477-2019}}</ref><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\" /> [[Fossil trackway|Trackways]] of sauropod and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as plant remains, are also known from the formation.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\">Weishampel, David B; et al. (2004). \"Dinosaur distribution (Early Cretaceous, Asia).\" In: Weishampel, David B.; Dodson, Peter; and Osm\u00f3lska, Halszka (eds.): The Dinosauria, 2nd, Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 563-570. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}.</ref> Fossils of non-dinosaurian fauna are represented by [[Ray finned fish|ray-finned fish]] like ''[[Lanxangichthys]]''<ref name=\":2\" /> and ''[[Lepidotes]]'', as well as turtles, including ''[[Shachemys]]'', ''[[Xinjiangchelys]]'', and an indeterminate [[carettochelyid]] and [[Trionychidae|trionychid]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Lapparent de Broin|first=France|date=2004-09-01|title=A new Shachemydinae (Chelonii, Cryptodira) from the Lower Cretaceous of Laos: preliminary data|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1631068304000934|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=3|issue=5|pages=387\u2013396|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2004.05.004|issn=1631-0683}}</ref> The [[Trigoniida|trigoniid]] [[Bivalvia|bivalves]] ''[[Trigonioides]]'' and ''[[Plicatounio]]'' have also been recovered from the formation.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation is the lateral equivalent of the neighboring Khok Kruat and [[Phu Phan Formation]]{{'}}s in Thailand; from the former of which fossils of theropods (including spinosaurids), sauropods, iguanodontians, and freshwater fish have also been recovered.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues suggested such a global distribution may have occurred earlier across [[Pangaea]], before its breakup starting in the [[Late Jurassic]], even if Asia became separated first.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In 2019, Spanish palaeontologist Elisabete Malafaia and colleagues also indicated a complex [[biogeographical]] pattern for spinosaurs during the Early Cretaceous, based on anatomical similarities between ''Ichthyovenator'' and ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Theropoda|T.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2154884}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2012]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Laos]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Aptian]]) {{fossilrange|125|113}}\n| image = Ichthyovenator laosensis.jpg\n| image_caption = Casts of the known [[spinal column]] at the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo. The thirteenth [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] spine and the lower part of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacrum]] have been partially reconstructed.\n| image_alt = White casts of fossil spinal column with a wave-like sail on display at a museum\n| taxon = Ichthyovenator\n| authority = Allain ''et al.'', [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Ichthyovenator laosensis'''''\n| type_species_authority = Allain ''et al.'', 2012\n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = \n}}\n\n'''''Ichthyovenator''''' is a [[genus]] of [[spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived in what is now Laos during the [[Aptian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]], sometime between 125 to 113 million years ago. It is known from [[Fossil|fossils]] collected in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]], the first of which were found in 2010, and comprised a partial skeleton without the skull or limbs. This specimen became the [[holotype]] of the new genus and [[species]] '''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''', and was described by [[palaeontologist]] Ronan Allain and colleagues in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]. The generic name, meaning \"fish hunter\", refers to its assumed [[piscivorous]] lifestyle, while the specific name alludes to the country of Laos. In 2014, it was announced that further remains from the dig site had been recovered; these fossils included teeth as well as more [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#vertebrae|vertebrae]] (backbones) and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubic bone]] from the same individual.\n\nThe holotype specimen is estimated to have been between {{convert|8.5 to 10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long and weighed {{convert|2 to 2.4|t|short ton|abbr=}}. ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s teeth were straight and conical, and its neck resembled that of the closely related ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''. Like others in its family, ''Ichthyovenator'' had tall [[neural spines]] forming a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back. Unlike other known spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail had a [[sinusoidal]] (wave-like) shape, curving downwards over the hips into two separate sails. The [[pelvic girdle]] was reduced, with the length ratio between the main body of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] and the pubes and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischium|ischia]] being higher than in any other known theropod dinosaurs. The animal was initially thought to belong to the [[Baryonychinae]] [[subfamily]], but more recent analyses place it as a primitive member in the [[Spinosaurinae]].\n\nAs a spinosaur, ''Ichthyovenator'' would have had a long, shallow snout and robust forelimbs. Its diet likely consisted mainly of aquatic prey (hence its etymology). Spinosaurids are also known to have eaten small dinosaurs and [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] in addition to fish. ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s conspicuous sail might have been used for [[sexual display]] or [[species recognition]]. Fossil evidence suggests that spinosaurids, especially spinosaurines, were adapted for [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. The vertebral spines of ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s tail were unusually tall, suggesting that\u2014as in today's [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]\u2014the tail may have aided in swimming. ''Ichthyovenator'' lived alongside [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as [[Bivalvia|bivalves]], fish and turtles.\n\n==Discovery and naming==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_skeletal_%26_size_comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|left|alt=Drawing of fossil rib, backbones and pelvis superimposed on silhouette of a dinosaur|Skeletal diagram with [[holotype]] elements in place, excluding the additional [[fossil]] material announced in 2014]]\n\nThe first [[fossil|fossils]] of ''Ichthyovenator'' were found in 2010 at [[Ban Kalum]], in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]] in [[Savannakhet Province]], Laos. These bones were recovered from a [[red sandstone]] layer, within a surface area of less than {{convert|2|m|ftin|sp=|abbr=}} squared. Designated under the specimen numbers MDS BK10-01 to 15, it consists of a partly [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#articulation|articulated]], well preserved skeleton lacking the skull and limbs, and including the third to last [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] (back) [[vertebra]], the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#neural spine|neural spine]] of the last dorsal vertebra, five partial [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacral]] (hip) vertebrae, the first two [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae, both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ilium|ilia]] (main hip bone), a right [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubis]] (pubic bone), both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischium|ischia]] (lower and rearmost hip bones) and a posterior dorsal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ribs|rib]]. The twelfth dorsal spine is bent sideways when viewed front-to-back due to [[Taphonomy|taphonomic]] distorsion, and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#centrum|centra]] (bodies of the vertebrae) of the sacrals are largely incomplete due to erosion, but preserved all their accompanying spines with their upper edges intact. At the time of ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description, excavations at the site were still ongoing.<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref>\n\nAfter undergoing preparation in 2011, the skeleton was used as the basis, or [[holotype]], for the [[type species]] ''Ichthyovenator laosensis''; named and described in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]] by [[palaeontologist|palaeontologists]] Ronan Allain, Tiengkham Xeisanavong, Philippe Richir, and Bounsou Khentavong. The [[Generic name (biology)|generic name]] is derived from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f30\u03c7\u03b8\u03cd\u03c2 (''ichthys''), \"fish\", and [[Latin]] ''venator'', \"hunter\", in reference to its likely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] refers to its provenance from Laos.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> ''Ichthyovenator'' is the third named [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] from Asia, after the Thai genus ''[[Siamosaurus]]'' in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], and the Chinese species \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' in [[2009 in archosaur paleontology|2009]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref>Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref><ref name=\"EBetal08\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B}}</ref> The latter may represent the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892|via=}}</ref>''\n\nIn 2014, a [[Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|''Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology'']] abstract on the genus was published by Allain. This abstract indicated that additional remains from the original individual had been found after an excavation in 2012. These remains include three teeth, the left pubis, and many vertebrae, including a nearly complete neck, the first dorsal vertebra, and seven more caudal vertebrae. However, this abstract has not been formally published as an academic paper as of 2020.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Some of these additional vertebrae were compared with those of other spinosaurids in a 2015 paper by German palaeontologist Serjoscha Evers and colleagues, in which they noted multiple similarities with the vertebrae of the African spinosaurid ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Evers|first=Serjoscha W.|last2=Rauhut|first2=Oliver W.M.|last3=Milner|first3=Angela C.|last4=McFeeters|first4=Bradley|last5=Allain|first5=Ronan|date=2015|title=A reappraisal of the morphology and systematic position of the theropod dinosaur Sigilmassasaurus from the \"middle\" Cretaceous of Morocco|url=|journal=PeerJ|language=en|volume=3|pages=e1323|doi=10.7717/peerj.1323|issn=2167-8359|pmc=4614847|pmid=26500829}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Spinosauridae_Size_Diagram_by_PaleoGeek_-_Version_2.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Silhouettes of five left-facing spinosaurid dinosaurs compared with a blue human to their left, Ichthyovenator in yellow, second from right|Size of various [[spinosaurid]]s (''Ichthyovenator'' in yellow, second from right) compared with a human|alt=]]\n\nIn 2016, American palaeontologist [[Gregory S. Paul]] estimated ''Ichthyovenator'' to have been approximately {{convert|8.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long and to have weighed {{convert|2|t|short ton|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=S.|first=Paul, Gregory|title=The Princeton field guide to dinosaurs|date=2016|publisher=|isbn=9781400883141|edition=2nd|location=Princeton, N.J.|pages=|oclc=954055249}}</ref> The same year, Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi gave a higher estimate of {{convert|10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=on}} in length, {{convert|2.95|m|ftin|sp=|abbr=on}} tall at the hips, and {{convert|2.4|t|short ton|abbr=on}} in weight.<ref>{{Cite book|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|last=Molina-P\u00e9rez & Larramendi|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=259}}</ref>\n\n''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s teeth were conical, straight, and bore no [[Serration|serrations]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The front carinae (edges) of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#maxilla|maxillary]] and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentary|dentary]] teeth were evident on the base of the [[tooth crown]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The front articulating surfaces of ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s rear cervical and front dorsal vertebrae were one and a half times wider than they were high and wider than the length of their centra. They also bore robust front [[Tubercle (bone)|tubercles]] ([[Process (anatomy)|processes]] for [[skeletal muscle]] attachment) and lacked inter[[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#zygapophyseal laminae|zygapophyseal laminae]], which resulted in their spinopre- and spinopostzygapophyseal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#fossae|fossae]] (depressions) having open undersides. The first dorsal vertebra had extensive [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#transverse processes|transverse processes]] (wing-like projections that articulate with the ribs), as well as deep air pockets at the front and back of its base. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#parapophyses|parapophysis]] (a process that articulated with the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#capitulum|capitulum]] of the ribs) of the first dorsal increased in height, with its underside remaining in contact with the front lower edge of the centrum. This is unlike the condition in most theropods, where the parapophyses shifted towards the top of the vertebra during the transition from cervical to dorsal vertebrae. All of these features were also present in ''Sigilmassasaurus''. ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s mid-cervical vertebrae all had elongate, somewhat wider than tall centra that became progressively shorter towards the rear of the neck, as well as well-developed keels on their bottom surfaces, traits all shared with the spinosaurids ''[[Baryonyx]], [[Suchomimus]]'', ''Sigilmassasaurus'',<ref name=\":1\" /> and ''[[Vallibonavenatrix]]''.<ref name=\":3\">Elisabete Malafaia; Jos\u00e9 Miguel Gasulla; Fernando Escaso; Iv\u00e1n Narv\u00e1ez; Jos\u00e9 Luis Sanz; Francisco Ortega (2019). \"A new spinosaurid theropod (Dinosauria: Megalosauroidea) from the late Barremian of Vallibona, Spain: Implications for spinosaurid diversity in the Early Cretaceous of the Iberian Peninsula\". Cretaceous Research. in press: 104221. {{doi|10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104221}}.</ref> The cervical neural spines of ''Ichthyovenator'' were taller than in ''Sigilmassasaurus'' and ''Baryonyx'', but shared the blade-like shape with those two taxa at the mid-cervicals.<ref name=\":1\" /> The single known dorsal rib, which was found near the twelfth dorsal vertebra, had a head typical of the ribs of other moderately to large-sized theropods. The rib shaft was strongly curved, forming a half circle. The lower end of the rib was slightly expanded both sideways and to the front and back. This condition, which differs from the tapered, pointed tips seen in the ribs of other known theropods, suggests that the rearmost dorsal ribs articulated with the complex of the [[sternum]] (breast bone).<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_65849.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Cast fossil spinal column laid out inside a glass display case at a museum|Casts of the [[Vertebra|vertebrae]] at the [[Mus\u00e9um national d'histoire naturelle|Mus\u00e9um National d'Histoire Naturelle]], Paris|alt=|left]]\n\nLike many other spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator'' had a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back and hips, formed by the elongated [[neural spines]] of its vertebrae. Uniquely among known members of the family however, ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s sail was divided in two over the hip, and had a [[sinusoid]] (wave-like) curvature. This is in contrast to the related genera ''[[Spinosaurus]]'' and ''Suchomimus'' (both of which had continuous sails that rose to a peak before sloping down again), and B''aryonyx'' (which showed a less developed sail, having much lower dorsal spines). ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s preserved dorsal and sacral [[spinal column]], over {{Convert|1|m||abbr=on}} long, shows a very high spine on the twelfth dorsal vertebra, representing a crest that rose from the back, and a lower rounded sail that extended from the sacral vertebrae of the hips, with its highest point above the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|54.6|cm||adj=on}} high spine of the twelfth dorsal vertebra widened towards the top, giving it a [[Trapezoid|trapezoidal]] shape, whereas the spines of other spinosaurids were roughly rectangular. It also lacked the forward or backward inclination of ''Spinosaurus''{{'}}s neural spines. Its front corner formed a {{Convert|3|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} narrow process, pointing upwards. The spine of the thirteenth dorsal vertebra has only been partly preserved, its upper and lower ends having broken off. From its general shape the describers inferred however, that it was about as long as the preceding spine. This would imply that the back edge of the front sail would form a rectangular corner, as the spine of the much lower first sacral vertebra is about {{Convert|21|cm||abbr=on}}, creating a sudden hiatus in the profile of the sail. The spine of the second sacral vertebra steeply curved upwards again, joining the {{Convert|39|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|48|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} high broad fan-shaped spines of the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|40|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} tall spine of the fifth sacral gradually descended. Unlike in most other theropods, including the sail of ''Suchomimus'', the sacral spines were not fused, nor did they have any extensive contacts. The second and third sacral centra were [[co-ossified]] (fused), with the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]] connecting them still visible. Since only the rearmost two dorsal vertebrae are preserved, it is unknown how far the dorsal sail continued towards the front of the animal's back.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour life reconstruction of a left-facing spinosaur|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]], with unknown regions such as the head and limbs based on relatives]]\n\nThe sacral sail was continued by the spines of the first two caudal vertebrae, which were {{Convert|28.4|cm||adj=|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|25.7|cm||adj=|abbr=on}} tall respectively. They leaned backwards at a 30 degree angle, and had smooth front and rear edges. The centra of the first two caudals were much broader than long and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#amphicoelous|amphicoelous]] (deeply concave on both ends). The caudal transverse processes were prominent, sturdy, and angled upwards towards the rear of the vertebrae. The transverse processes of the first caudal vertebra, when seen from above, had a [[Sigmoid function|sigmoid]] (or S-shaped) profile. The prespinal and postspinal fossae (bony depressions in front and behind the neural spines) were confined to above the base of the neural spines. The sides of the first caudal were also deeply hollowed out between the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#Prezygapophyses|prezygapophyses]] (articular surfaces with the neural arch of the preceding vertebra) and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#diapophyses|diapophyses]] (processes on the sides for rib articulation), a condition not observed in other theropods.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Some of the caudal vertebrae also had unusually tall, forwardly-extended prezygapophyses.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe {{Convert|92|cm||adj=on|abbr=on}} ilium of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] was blade-like, and longer in proportion to the pubic bone, which was {{Convert|65|cm||adj=|abbr=on}} long, than in any other known large theropod. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#postacetabular process|postacetabular ala]] (front expansion) was much longer than the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#preacetabular process|preacetabular ala]] (rear expansion), the latter had a shelf on its central surface, which formed the middle edge of the preacetabular fossa. Viewed distally (from away from the centre of attachment), the lower end of the pubis was L-shaped, resembling that of ''Baryonyx''. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic apron|pubic apron]] (the expanded lower end of the pubis) features a large [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic foramen|pubic foramen]]. On the hind rim of the pubic bone, two openings, the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#obturator%20foramen|obturator foramen]] and a lower [[fenestra]] (opening), were not fully closed, making them into notches. The ischium was {{Convert|49.6|cm|in|adj=|abbr=on}} long, making it shorter in relation to the pubis than in all other known [[Tetanurae|tetanuran]] theropods. Its main body was large and extensive, atypical of the Y-shaped upper ischia of other tetanurans, and bore an oval-shaped obturator foramen in its side. The shaft of the ischium was flattened sideways, and had an unexpanded [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischiadic apron|ischiadic apron]] (as in ''[[Monolophosaurus]]'' and ''[[Sinraptor]]'').<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> The ischium attached to the illium via a peg-and-socket-like articulation, unlike the flat and concave condition seen in ''Baryonyx''. This feature was also present in ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:20130825_Brazil_Rio_de_Janeiro_0144.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Reconstructed skeleton of a spinosaurid holding a pterosaur skeleton in its jaws against a painted backdrop|Reconstructed skeleton of the [[spinosaurine]] ''[[Irritator]]'', mounted at the [[National Museum of Rio de Janeiro]]]]\n\nAllain and his team considered ''Ichthyovenator'' as representing the first unequivocal spinosaurid from Asia.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Though prior spinosaurids had been named from the continent; including ''Siamosaurus'' from the [[Barremian]] [[Sao Khua Formation]] of Thailand, and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' from the [[Aptian]] [[Xinlong Formation]] of China, the authors noted that the validity of these taxa has been debated by palaeontologists, due to them only being confidently known from isolated teeth.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\" /> In 2017, Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Caesar Schultz suggested that these teeth may eventually be attributed to spinosaurids similar to ''Ichthyovenator''.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966}}</ref> However, American researcher Mickey Mortimer pointed out that a spinosaurid skeleton, possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus'', was excavated from the Thai [[Khok Kruat Formation]] in 2004,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and identified as a definite spinosaur in a 2008 conference abstract by British palaeontologist [[Angela Milner]] and colleagues.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> Mortimer stated that even if teeth are ruled out, confirmed evidence of spinosaurids in Asia was known eight years before ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s description.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2012, ''Ichthyovenator'' was assigned by Allain and colleagues to the Spinosauridae, more precisely to the subfamily [[Baryonychinae]] in a [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] position as the [[sister species]] of a [[clade]] formed by ''Baryonyx'' and ''Suchomimus''. The describers established the following [[autapomorphies]] (unique derived traits) in ''Ichthyovenator'': its dorsal and sacral sinusoidal sail; the thirteenth dorsal neural spine being 410% the length of the centrum, and having a distinct finger-shaped [[Process (anatomy)|process]] on its front upper corner; the broad, expanded tips of the third and fourth sacral spines; the first caudal vertebra's deep prezygapophyseal centrodiapophyseal fossae and S-shaped transverse processes in top view; and the lengthy illium, with its accompanying pubis being shorter in comparison to it than in any other known theropod. Allain and colleagues also identified some anatomical features unique among tetanuran theropods, including the rearmost dorsal ribs articulating with the sternal complex, the pubis's main body having obturator and pubic openings, and the ischium having a foramen on its upper end, as well as a shaft that was flatenned sideways. The shrinking of the pubis and ischium relative to the pelvis has been observed in basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaurs]] and [[Allosauroidea|allosauroids]], which the describers attributed to [[mosaic evolution]]: the evolution of certain anatomical traits at different times in separate species.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> \n\n[[File:Spinosauridae_\"Sails\"_Comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Three pairs of illustrated fossil pelvic bones and spinal columns compared to the silhouette of a human to their left, Ichthyovenator's pelvis and vertebrae first from the bottom|Comparison of the [[pelvic region]] and [[Neural spine sail|neural spine sails]] of ''[[Suchomimus]]'', ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', and ''Ichthyovenator'']]\n\nIn 2014, Allain's abstract instead found that ''Ichthyovenator'' was part of the subfamily [[Spinosaurinae]], due to the lack of serrations on its teeth and the possession of vertebrae with some similarities to those of ''Sigilmassasaurus''.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2015, a [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] analysis by Evers and colleagues suggested that given the apparent presence of both baryonychine and spinosaurine characteristics in ''Ichthyovenator'', the distinction between the two subfamilies may not be as clear as previously thought.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mortimer hypothesized in 2017 that ''Ichthyovenator'' may not have been a spinosaurid at all, instead possibly being a sail-backed [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] dinosaur closely related to ''[[Concavenator]]''. She thus placed ''Ichthyovenator'' as [[Incertae sedis|''incertae sedis'']] (of uncertain taxonomic affinity) within the clade [[Orionides]], pending description of the new material, which she states will likely confirm ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s spinosaurid identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Ichthyovenatorlaosensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=2017|website=The Theropod Database}}</ref> A 2017 analysis by Sales and Schultz questioned Baryonychinae's validity, citing the [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of Brazilian spinosaurids ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Angaturama'' as suggesting they were possible [[Transitional fossil|transitionary forms]] between the earlier baryonychines and the later spinosaurines. The authors thus indicated that with further research, Baryonychinae may turn out to be a [[paraphyletic]] (unnatural) grouping.<ref name=\":17\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s spinosaurine classification was supported by British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues in 2018, who resolved it as a basal member of the group due to its tall dorsal sail. Their [[cladogram]] can be seen below:<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2018|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1=''[[Siamosaurus suteethorni]]''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1='''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\n\n== Palaeobiology ==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator vertebrae.jpg|thumb|alt=White casts of spinal column with wave-like sail laid out on a dark background in a museum exhibit|Casts of the vertebrae seen from behind]]\n\nThough no skull remains have been found for ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had elongated, low and narrow snouts which allowed them to reach far for food and close their jaws quickly, akin to modern [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]. The tips of their upper and lower jaws fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape that bore long teeth, behind which there was a notch in the upper jaw; this formed a natural trap for prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s straight and unserrated teeth,<ref name=\":0\" /> like those of other spinosaurids, would have been suitable for impaling and capturing small animals and aquatic prey. This type of jaw and tooth morphology, also observed in today's [[gharials]] and other fish-eating predators, has led many palaeontologists to believe that spinosaurids were largely piscivorous (as implied in ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s name).<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cuff|first=Andrew R.|last2=Rayfield|first2=Emily J.|date=2013|title=Feeding Mechanics in Spinosaurid Theropods and Extant Crocodilians|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=8|issue=5|pages=e65295|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0065295|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3665537|pmid=23724135|bibcode=2013PLoSO...865295C}}</ref> This is also evidenced by ''[[Scheenstia]]'' fish scales discovered in the stomach cavity of one ''Baryonyx'' skeleton,<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=L\u00f3pez-Arbarello|first1=A.|year=2012|title=Phylogenetic Interrelationships of Ginglymodian Fishes (Actinopterygii: Neopterygii)|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=7|issue=7|pages=e39370|bibcode=2012PLoSO...739370L|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0039370|pmc=3394768|pmid=22808031}}</ref> and a ''Spinosaurus'' snout found with a vertebra from the [[sawfish]] ''[[Onchopristis]]'' embedded in it.<ref name=\"dalsassoetal05\">{{cite journal|last=dal Sasso|first=C.|author2=Maganuco, S.|author3=Buffetaut, E.|author4=Mendez, M.A.|year=2005|title=New information on the skull of the enigmatic theropod ''Spinosaurus'', with remarks on its sizes and affinities|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume=25|issue=4|pages=888\u2013896|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2005)025[0888:NIOTSO]2.0.CO;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> A more [[generalist diet]] for spinosaurs has also been proposed, based on fossils such as juvenile ''[[Iguanodon]]'' bones also found in the aforementioned ''Baryonyx'' specimen, and an ''Irritator'' tooth embedded in the vertebrae of a [[pterosaur]]. Thus, it is likely that spinosaurids were also scavengers and hunters of larger prey than fish.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"milner2007\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Andrew|last2=Kirkland|first2=James|date=September 2007|title=The case for fishing dinosaurs at the St. George Dinosaur Discovery Site at Johnson Farm|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285906225|journal=Utah Geological Survey Notes|volume=39|pages=1\u20133|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sales|first1=M. A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=M. B.|last3=Horn|first3=B. L. D.|last4=de Oliveira|first4=I. A. P.|last5=Schultz|first5=C. L.|last6=Bibi|first6=F.|date=2016|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmc=4734717|pmid=26829315|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref> Though no limb bones are known from ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had well-built arms with enlarged thumb claws, which they likely used to hunt and process prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> \n\n[[File:CrocoLoco-swimming-01.jpg|thumb|left|Three images of a crocodile in the water at different stages of swimming sequence as it propels itself with its tail|''Ichthyovenator'' might have used its tail, which had elongated neural spines, for propulsion through water, similar to [[crocodilians]] such as this [[Nile crocodile]]<ref name=\"arden2018\" />]]\n\nMany possible functions, including [[thermoregulation]] and energy storage, have been proposed for spinosaurid sails.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"JBB97\">{{cite journal|last=Bailey|first=J.B.|year=1997|title=Neural spine elongation in dinosaurs: sailbacks or buffalo-backs?|journal=Journal of Paleontology|volume=71|issue=6|pages=1124\u20131146|doi=10.1017/S0022336000036076|jstor=1306608}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues posited that given the high diversity in neural spine elongation observed in different theropod dinosaurs, as well as [[histological]] research done on the sails of [[Synapsid|synapsids]] (stem mammals), ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s sinusoidal sail may have instead been used for [[courtship display]] or for [[Species recognition|recognising members of its own species]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In a 2013 blog post, British palaeontologist [[Darren Naish]] considered the latter function unlikely, favouring the hypothesis of [[sexual selection]] for ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s sail, since it appears to have evolved on its own, without very close relatives. Naish also notes that it is possible that similar relatives have not been discovered yet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/tetrapod-zoology/species-recognition-vs-sexual-selection-in-dinosaurs/|title=Dinosaurs and their exaggerated structures : species recognition aids, or sexual display devices?|last=Naish|first=Darren|date=2013|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nSpinosaurids appear to have had [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles, spending much of their time near or in water, as has been inferred by the high density of their limb bones (which would have made them less [[Buoyancy|buoyant]]), and the [[Isotope ratio|isotope ratios]] of their teeth being closer to those of aquatic animals like turtles, crocodilians, and hippopotamuses than those of other, more terrestrial theropods.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Semiaquatic adaptations seem to have been more developed in spinosaurines than baryonychines.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /><ref name=\"Holtz 1998\">{{Cite journal|last1=Holtz Jr.|first1=T. R.|year=1998|title=Spinosaurs as crocodile mimics|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ac3ac036aeff2608055324d2f1186e8359059706|journal=Science|volume=282|issue=5392|pages=1276\u20131277|doi=10.1126/science.282.5392.1276}}</ref><ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=N.|last2=Sereno|first2=P. C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=C.|last4=Maganuco|first4=S.|last5=Fabri|first5=M.|last6=Martill|first6=D. M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=S.|last8=Myhrvold|first8=N.|last9=Lurino|first9=D. A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20131616|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref> ''Ichthyovenator''{{'}}s short pubis and ischium relative to its illium, coupled with the elongated neural spines in the tails of early spinosaurs, were suggested by Arden and colleagues in 2018 as indications that spinosaurids may have progressively employed further use of their tails to propel themselves underwater (similarly to crocodilians) as they grew more adapted towards an aquatic lifestyle.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /> A similar, though more extreme shrinkage of the pelvis and hind limbs was observed in ''Spinosaurus'', which appears to have been more semiaquatic than any other known spinosaur species.<ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_20142\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=Nizar|last2=Sereno|first2=Paul C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=Cristiano|last4=Maganuco|first4=Simone|last5=Fabri|first5=Matteo|last6=Martill|first6=David M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=Samir|last8=Myhrvold|first8=Nathan|last9=Lurino|first9=Dawid A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20136|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref>\n\n== Palaeoecology and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Caudal vertebrae Tangvayosaurus hoffeti.jpg|thumb|Fossils of the [[sauropod]] ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'', another dinosaur from the [[Gres superieurs Formation]], [[Savannakhet]] Dinosaur Museum]]\n\n''Ichthyovenator'' is known from the Barremian to [[Cenomanian]] Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation, and was found in a layer probably dating to the Aptian [[Stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], between 125 to 113 million years ago.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> It coexisted with other dinosaurs such as the [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'', and an indeterminate sauropod, [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]], and [[neoceratopsian]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Cavin|first=Lionel|last2=Deesri|first2=Uthumporn|last3=Veran|first3=Monette|last4=Khentavong|first4=Bounsou|last5=Jintasakul|first5=Pratueng|last6=Chanthasit|first6=Phornphen|last7=Allain|first7=Ronan|date=2019-03-04|title=A new Lepisosteiformes (Actinopterygii: Ginglymodi) from the Early Cretaceous of Laos and Thailand, SE Asia|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=17|issue=5|pages=393\u2013407|doi=10.1080/14772019.2018.1426060|issn=1477-2019}}</ref><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\" /> [[Fossil trackway|Trackways]] of sauropod and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as plant remains, are also known from the formation.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\">Weishampel, David B; et al. (2004). \"Dinosaur distribution (Early Cretaceous, Asia).\" In: Weishampel, David B.; Dodson, Peter; and Osm\u00f3lska, Halszka (eds.): The Dinosauria, 2nd, Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 563-570. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}.</ref> Fossils of non-dinosaurian fauna are represented by [[Ray finned fish|ray-finned fish]] like ''[[Lanxangichthys]]''<ref name=\":2\" /> and ''[[Lepidotes]]'', as well as turtles, including ''[[Shachemys]]'', ''[[Xinjiangchelys]]'', and an indeterminate [[carettochelyid]] and [[Trionychidae|trionychid]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Lapparent de Broin|first=France|date=2004-09-01|title=A new Shachemydinae (Chelonii, Cryptodira) from the Lower Cretaceous of Laos: preliminary data|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1631068304000934|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=3|issue=5|pages=387\u2013396|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2004.05.004|issn=1631-0683}}</ref> The [[Trigoniida|trigoniid]] [[Bivalvia|bivalves]] ''[[Trigonioides]]'' and ''[[Plicatounio]]'' have also been recovered from the formation.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation is the lateral equivalent of the neighboring Khok Kruat and [[Phu Phan Formation]]{{'}}s in Thailand; from the former of which fossils of theropods (including spinosaurids), sauropods, iguanodontians, and freshwater fish have also been recovered.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues suggested such a global distribution may have occurred earlier across [[Pangaea]], before its breakup starting in the [[Late Jurassic]], even if Asia became separated first.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In 2019, Spanish palaeontologist Elisabete Malafaia and colleagues also indicated a complex [[biogeographical]] pattern for spinosaurs during the Early Cretaceous, based on anatomical similarities between ''Ichthyovenator'' and ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Theropoda|T.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2154884}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2012]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Laos]]\n", "name_user": "PaleoGeekSquared", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClassification:Fixed duplink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ichthyovenator"}
{"title_page": "Feminist performance art", "text_new": "{{essay-like|date=November 2017}}\nAccording to scholar Virginia Mackenny, [[performance art]] is a great tool to mold and remold gender because performance art, in most instances, includes a direct subversion to everyday conventions. MacKenny also writes that feminist performance Art had a large presence \u201cin the late '60s and early '70s in America when, in the climate of protest constituted by the civil rights movement and [[second wave feminism]].\" There are several movements that fall under the category of feminist performance art, including Feminist Postmodernism, which took place during 1960-1970 and focused on the exploitation of women's bodies as a means for profit. Similarly, the Chicanx movement emerged in East Los Angeles during the 1970s, and focused on the Vietnam war, which was considered a post-apartheid movement.<ref name=\"MacKenny\">{{cite journal|last1=MacKenny|first1=Virginia|title=Post - Apartheid Performance Art as a Site of Gender Resistance|journal=Agenda Empowering Women for Gender Equity|date=2001|volume=49|pages=15\u201324|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n== Feminist Postmodernism ==\nAs Forte writes in her analysis of feminist performance art in the 1960s and 1970s, \u201cWithin this movement, women's performance emerges as a specific strategy that allies [[postmodernism]] and [[feminism]] \u2026 women used performance as a deconstructive strategy to demonstrate the objectification of women and its results\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Forte|first1=Jeanie|title=Women's Performance Art: Feminism and Postmodernism|journal=Theatre Journal|date=1988|volume=40.2|issn=0192-2882}}</ref> Another strategy that was commonly used by feminist performance artists during the postmodernist movement was \u201cremoving of the mask,\u201d which was utilized to demonstrate the consequences of female representations in the media, on the psyche of women. MacKenny also writes about the removing of the mask within Feminist Postmodernism. She writes, \u201cThis 'masquerade' or 'masking' occurs when women play with their assigned gender roles in multiple, often contradictory ways - adopting, adapting, overlaying and subverting the hegemonic discourse in the process.\u201d\n\n== Chicanx Movement ==\nDuring the late 1960s and early 1970s in East Los Angeles, protests broke out against the [[Vietnam War]] and its disproportionate death rate of 22% Chicanx people, while the percentage of the population that Chicanx people made up only 5% of the United States entire population.\n[[Asco (art collective)]], based in [[East Los Angeles, California|East LA]] commented on the impacts of the war on [[queer]] and brown identities, as well as the tragedies that occurred in the protests discussed above due to [[police brutality]]. The collective created visual and performative art. Some of their most famous performances experiment with gender roles, for example, one male identifying artist attended a club wearing \u201cbooty shorts, pink platforms, and a shirt that said \u2018just turned 21.\u2019\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perez|first1=Laura E.|title=Chicana art: the politics of spiritual and aesthetic altarities|date=2007|publisher=Durham: Duke U|isbn=978-0-8223-8988-0|doi=10.1215/9780822389880}}</ref>\nThe group continued to make performance and visual art that engaged with concepts related to queer and [[ethnic identity]] in East LA. During this period, East LA was ghettoized through a border of highways and dilapidated conditions.\n\n== Post Apartheid Movement ==\nMacKenny writes about two of the major players in the Post [[Apartheid]] performance art movement in [[South Africa]]. She first writes about Carol Anne Gainer and her performance entitled 'Exposed.' MacKenny explains that Gainer disrupts and subverts the binary as she performs as both the model and artist in this performance, which works to blur the \"distinction between artist/art, artist/model, constructor/constructed, finder/found, mind/body, subject/object.\"\nThe second artist which Mackenny writes about is a [[mixed race]] artist who performs a piece called 'Span.' MacKenny asserts that the artist Tracey Rose, alludes to Western societies exploitation of people of colour in scientific study and analysis, and the \"dissection and embalming of body parts of native 'others' (the most pertinent to the South African context being Saartje Baartman, a young Khoisan woman displayed for her unique genitalia and steatopygia, or enlarged buttocks),\" through her own display of her body.<ref name=\"MacKenny\"/> Her performance exposes her naked body and is contrasted against images of \"scientific\" exploitation, which both highlights the dichotomy between these subjects and engages with Mackenny's definition of post-apartheid performance art and its political aim to blur and disrupt binary structures.\n\n=== Anti War Performance Art Movement ===\nThe sociologist Rachel V Kutz-Flamenbaum writes about two major players in the anti-war performance art movement during the George W Bush administration. Code Pink, and Raging Grannies challenge and subvert gender norms in their performances, and thus, use very similar tactics and strategies. For instance, in Code Pink, Kutz-Flamenbaum asserts that, \"the emphasis on women\u2019s role as pacifist caregivers presents a nonthreatening image of women activists.\" \n\nThe perpetuated concept of women as non threatening, relies on the audiences association of pink as a non threatening and feminized colour. Kutz-Flamenbaum argues that \"Code Pink\u2019s use of civil disobedience and aggressive trailing of public officials confound and challenge normative gender expectations of women as passive, polite, and well-behaved.\"(95)<ref name=\"Kutz-Flamenbaum\">{{cite journal|last1=Kutz-Flamenbaum|first1=Rachel V|title=Code Pink, Raging Grannies, and the Missile Dick Chicks: Feminist Performance Activism in the Contemporary Anti-War Movement|journal=NWSA Journal|date=Spring 2001|volume=19|issue=1|pages=90\u201396|issn=1040-0656}}</ref>\nKutz-Flamenbaum claims that [[Raging Grannies]] similarly use this tactic in the description of their mission statement. Kutz-Flamenbaum explains that their mission statement \"illustrates the way Raging Grannies use norm- embracing stereotypes of 'little old ladies' and 'grannies' to challenge the gendered assumptions of their audiences.\" Their conscious performance as non-threatening and nurturing women, strategically and tactfully confront issues related to war and challenge the participation of the George W Bush administration in the war. \n\n== Performance Artists ==\n\n==[[Yoko Ono]]==\n\n=== Overview ===\nOno belonged to a generation of early feminist performance artists but is unique among them for her international fame as [[John Lennon]]\u2019s wife in the late 60s and 70s.  During their courtship the couple manipulated the press attention directed on them by documenting their relationship through performance art.<ref name=\":0\">Elizabeth Ann Lindau. \u201cMother Superior\u201d: Maternity and Creativity in the Work of Yoko Ono.\" ''Women and Music: A Journal of Gender and Culture'' 20 (University of Nebraska Press: 2016), 64.</ref> As Ono stated in a 1986 TV interview, \u201cwe were always together\u2026 we exchanged very fully between ourselves.\u201d<ref name=\":1\">''Yoko Ono on John Lennon's Assasination, Their Son Sean and Influencing The Beatles Breakup.'', ''YouTube'' (YouTube, 2017), <nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Suj8MCysBKQ</nowiki>)</ref> They emphasized this unusual situation, where the husband and wife worked together rather than the pair working separately outside the home, through their performance art \u201cBed-ins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs an interracial couple they also challenged racial stereotypes. She confessed, \u201cI think it was a big lesson for the world that we were together\u2026 And I think it might have helped too for people to understand what it means to confront the interracial couple.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nParenthood is a factor in the controversy surrounding Ono. Women were not usually part of performance art or rock music, and mothers in particular were antithetical to everything rock stood for. The public idea of rock music as youthful male rebellion placed mothers as the opponent. When Ono and Lennon began their relationship, Beatles fans saw this female influence as an intrusion and the force that broke up their favorite band. However, as Ono saw it, the [[The Beatles|Beatles]] grew apart naturally and she was not the primary cause.<ref name=\":1\" /> Public confusion was exacerbated with Ono\u2019s pregnancy. While pregnant with their son Sean, Ono announced to Lennon: \u201cI am carrying the baby nine months and that is enough. You take care of it afterwards.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> After Sean\u2019s birth, she ran the couple\u2019s business while Lennon stayed home as \u201chousehusband.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Ono\u2019s hands off approach to parenting is a source of controversy because she was simultaneously too motherly and not motherly enough.\n\n=== Work ===\nOne of her early works is [[Cut Piece]], first performed in 1964 at the Yamaichi Concert Hall in Kyoto. She kneeled on the stage in her best suit and invited audience members to use scissors to cut it off of her. Confronting issues of gender, class and cultural identity, Ono sat silently until the piece concluded at her discretion.<ref>Munroe, Alexandra; Ono, Yoko; Hendricks, Jon; Altshuler, Bruce; Ross, David A.; Wenner, Jann S.; Concannon, Kevin C.; Tomii, Reiko; Sayle, Murray; Gomez, Edward M. (October 2000). Yes Yoko Ono. New York: Harry N. Abrams. {{ISBN|0-81094-587-8}}.</ref> Ono also published a book of conceptual art in 1964, entitled [[Grapefruit (book)|Grapefruit]]. The book reads like an instruction manual for the reader to create their own versions of her pieces either physically or in the imagination. Over the nearly 60 years that she has been active, Ono has created installations of modern art across the globe, recorded numerous original songs both with John Lennon and the [[Plastic Ono Band]], as well as individually, and continues in activism to this day.\n\n== Orlan==\nORLAN (born as Mireille Suzanne Francette Porte) is French performance artist, most known for her radical use of plastic surgery to form her work. She uses her face and body as a malleable tool to change her appearance and therefore change her art. She primarily used plastic surgery to morph and change her body in her theatrical expression. Orlan uses her body at the heart of her expression, to articulate her political, social and cultural beliefs. Due to suffering an ectopic pregnancy, she felt her body was changed dramatically, and through that, she chose to turn her body into artwork through the use of plastic surgery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/orlan/|title=ORLAN {{!}} artnet|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOne of her most notable performances was that of the 1977 International Contemporary Art Fair in Paris. On her exterior, she had a large photo of a torso on her chest. This was turned into a slot machine, where the audience could put a coin down the slot and watch it descend into the groin. As a reward, that audience member were given a kiss. She also displayed her sexual organs during menstruation under a magnifying glass for respective audience members to study. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Donger|first=Simon|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XoXFBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=orlan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyw_Da7snoAhVxlFwKHZmmAdsQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=orlan&f=false|title=ORLAN: A Hybrid Body of Artworks|last2=Shepherd|first2=Simon|date=2010-05-20|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-97128-0|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Bj\u00f6rk Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir ==\nThe musical artist Bj\u00f6rk has been challenging musical barriers since her time in the band [[The Sugarcubes]], which became the biggest alternative rock band in Iceland. She has since gone on to a solo career, starting in 1993 with the album [[Debut (Bj\u00f6rk album)|''Debut'']] with her last album having been released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bj%C3%B6rk-mn0000769444/biography|title=Bj\u00f6rk {{!}} Biography & History|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> She throughout her time has used her music to speak on matters she deemed important while following a unique and individualistic style for each of her albums. She finds something that she finds challenging or that she dislikes and work with it to create something she's proud of, allowing her to continue having these unique albums.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4143741-interview--bjork-talks-piracy-punk-lady-gaga-and-biophilia|title=Interview: Bjork talks piracy, punk, Lady Gaga and Biophilia|last=October 9th|first=Kevin EG Perry|last2=2011|website=DrownedInSound|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== ''Biophilia and Environmental Work'' ===\nThis has lead to one of her most famous albums ''[[Biophilia (album)|Biophilia]]'' which was Bj\u00f6rk's two year long passion project to give her music a more visual and hands on feel. The album was developed into an iPad and iPod app that allowed users to listen to each song while playing games that visually showcased the music. The most notable example is the song \u2018Thunderbolt\u2019  which allows listeners to draw \"Tesla coil charges which alter the bass lines you hear\" and when she performs the song live she has twin Tesla coils to play the bass line.<ref name=\":2\" /> This album however was more than a challenge for Bj\u00f6rk to create a new sound, she created the album as a response to the environmental issues Iceland was facing in 2008. Iceland had allowed the aluminum smelters to take over the countries fishing industry while being the cause for excessive greenhouse gas emissions. Her goal was to create an album that could educate people about the world we are living in and inspire them to take actions against companies that work to destroy the planet.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/07/bjork-environmental-campaign-timetable-nordic-schools|title=Bj\u00f6rk's environmental campaign goes on the timetable in Nordic schools|date=2014-06-07|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=arts|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|last3=correspondent|first3=media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/11/13/bjork-wages-battle-against-icelandic-aluminum/|title=Bj\u00f6rk Wages Battle Against Icelandic Aluminum|last=Kanter|first=James|date=2008-11-13|website=Green Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== 'Declare Independence' and Activism ===\nThis environmental work would not be the only time she has used her music and voice to speak out as the song 'Declare Independence' would often be a song she would use to speak out for the freedom of nations trying to seceded from the nations they have been forced to be apart of. Most notable was when she, unauthorized, sang the song in her Shanghai concert in 2008, chanting Tibet in the middle of the song.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7276891.stm|title=Bjork makes 'free Tibet' gesture|date=2008-03-04|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> At the time Tibet was revolting against China for its freedom, and as such her use of the song caused many concert goers to leave the venue and the Chinese government to tighten their regulations for all outside performers from then on. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7293605.stm|title=Western acts 'welcome' in China|date=2008-03-13|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Lady Gaga ==\nLady Gaga (Stefani Joanne Angelina Germanotta) has experimented and incorporated performance art into her life. Her first internet appearance in performance art came in 2013 in a kickstarter for \u201cThe Abromovic Method\u201d ran by Marina Abromovic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/71937056|title=The Abramovic Method Practiced by Lady Gaga|website=Vimeo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>This video was taken during a physical and spiritual retreat she participated that was hosted by Abromovic at her summer home. Gaga is featured \u201cfilling the room\u201d with her voice and wandering naked in the woods. Gaga was asked to test her body and go through strenuous activities. She also added to the piece by participating fully and even suggesting additions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://culturacolectiva.com/art/lady-gaga-marina-abramovic-collaboration|title=The Day Lady Gaga Stripped To Please Marina Abramovic and Be Free From Drugs|date=2017-01-30|website=culturacolectiva.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Abbromovic reported she was a very compliant student. Later, Gaga fit performance art into her 2011 Video Music Awards appearance. She showed up to perform her song \u201cYou and I\u201d dressed up as a person deemed Jo Calderone. <ref>{{Citation|title=Jo Calderone (Lady Gaga) You And I Live - VMAs 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SkWoA25V4tQ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> When speaking, she spoke with a Brooklyn accent and walk, and spoke as a typical man. She commented that performance art meant fully committing and diving into a character including, acting as the character the whole night. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1669957/lady-gaga-jo-calderone-vmas/|title=Why Did Lady Gaga Go To VMAs As Jo Calderone?|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>They finished their speech at the award show talking about the importance of accepting people for who they are with no discrimination, because it was they way they were born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-339-1286022|title=Lady Gaga performs as male alter ego Jo Calderone at MTV VMAs {{!}} NME|date=2011-08-29|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Later Gaga dabbled with the performance art of \u201cCamp\u201d at the 2019 Met Gala. \"Camp\" is a form of performance art through clothing that stems from the drag culture and is meant to tell a story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://depauliaonline.com/41447/artslife/camp-the-theme-that-means-the-most-or-nothing-at-all/|title=Camp: the theme that means the most \u2013 or nothing at all|last=Oxnevad|first=Emma|date=2019-05-13|website=The DePaulia|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance through clothing ====\nHer outfit for the Met Gala consisted of four overlapping outfits that she stripped from one to the next while on the red carpet for the Gala.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peters|first=Micheal A|date=January 2012|title=On the Edge of Theory: Lady Gaga, performance and cultural theory|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwVV3NCsIwDC6yg7_vEPAkOLGuW1tvIv6B4EW9jmzddlNxevDtTdyGeuolCaVNkyZNvnaFR3Fr1hKdmYy48yOcefywq_hcBbrd5D8YZ0YF045YHC5Adx3g9BFcc_g08L3msEf3gg0WOIbbt4YeKL6GBpSipu0L73F_ZoNq6InTenVcbv36MwG_YFAqPzQJ6Sqiy6RLlMxDY8n1WtQBzVBl1jolU0PeNpeJY5ASIjaJZguvXW74Y91hJbcx2XG92-UHZNNMtY0YfHBSUbF9j1lJHndMsa51p4VhuKV4wWIVO1NiGP0xcIU6meUCn2UZ7w7nX9o339xjrg|journal=Contemporary readings in Law and social Justice|volume=4|pages=1|via=}}</ref> The outfits consisted of black and pink and had a coy, classic femme aesthetic.She also had a team providing her with props like a suitcase, wagon and 90\u2019s telephone. She also represented performance art on a mainstream platform with two separate VMA appearances. One was in 2010, when she wore a \u201cmeat dress\u201d to the show. The dress consisted of prime rib and flank steak. The dress was referencing a speech \u201cThe Prime Rib of America\u201d, that encouraged the end of discrimination against gay men and women in the military and Gaga stated the military denies them \u201c the greatest cut of meat my country has to offer.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/lady-gaga-meat-dress-explanation|title=Getting Political|website=British Vogue|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The second was the Joe Calerone one previously mentioned, both performed with intent of raising awareness to a cause.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kumari|first=Ashanka|date=April 2016|title=\"You and I\"|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMw42JgAfZbUxkgJ4GCF80UJJfqAasRA1Mm0NmlJga6ppbGwDwEPcUb2MPggBWdwNaEASdDwKOGOZH5h_coAPvSCp6PGuZaKUB3rVaChYAtI4UAxLJ6hfw0heDUnDSFzDwFn8SUSgX3xPREsELwJpDkwyt5GFhKikpTeSEUN0Oom2uIs4cu9LYBXVCVZ6prngwszFMNLcyTjdIsDI2TzE2SUlIsLU2NUkySk43NTYEJNTHVJDUl0SQ5CbQdNBlYV6aapYAyhWliYhro4nUtiLmw-i2-AHJgRDy8oQ0MiXhwSAAVq0IVo0x2xyeCphvig4ANKVDWAF2iZAhRB2454zEx3ivAORRiNgDmtXCK|journal=The Journal of Pop Culture|volume=49|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance of her own feminism ====\nShe preaches about equality to all through the removing of labels and just treating people as people. Her main message is to spread kindness over all else.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jennex|first=Craig|date=July 2013|title=Diva Worship and the Sonic Search for Queer Utopia|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwfV09DwIhDCXmBj__A4sjBo7qweTgR1z9uDgSUEicNOb090vhjLo4sRRIF9pH2_f6pIi41ZN2Sg1prGXijMF-ACEnlVZTgE4aU-RMVKIs0j8_Z2jT_TyiHHqkXF6elh6vqaOXRmhNY1ZE90gaS3M7Lo2pHd1GzHendXO9XeyQFM394Ud5GZB6vTosNqxVFmAnyRWwADNnBaCanXBVlVjDtJKOSzs7O-twHFW7ABq8kFaBdlB6OPMgrPcyoMg65HPfsczcMjmEEW_OzdZrg16b7HXcNm63_ZS4jcUig9nFbD3Gb4V282z3zZ5qmoThQxbcMPLvTS-VRmpL|journal=Popular Music and Society: Fandom|volume=36|pages=3|via=}}</ref> She believes women have the right to choose the life they see fit for themselves, even if it means dependent on others. She is also a big advocate for sexual assault awareness as she is a survivor herself. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Corona|first=Victor P.|date=2013|title=Memory, Monsters, and Lady Gaga|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|journal=The Journal of Popular Culture|language=en|volume=46|issue=4|pages=725\u2013744|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|issn=1540-5931}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== The Guerrilla Girls ==\nThe Guerrilla Girls formed in New York City in the mid 1980s.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/guerrilla-girls-6858|title=Guerrilla Girls|last=Tate|website=Tate|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>The Guerrilla Girls focused their performances, protests, installations, and exhibits on highlighting the lack of representation of women and people of color within the art world.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> Most notably, The Guerrilla Girls donned gorilla masks and costumes during protest in order to maintain anonymity, and to make their work more about the issues rather than each member\u2019s own identity.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nAfter protesting the lack of diversity at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City in 1985, the Guerrilla Girls expanded their work into prints, billboards, public commissions, and, indoor exhibitions. This also came with their work focusing on a wider array of issues such as the wage gap, tokenism, and funding for the arts.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> The public performances of the Guerrilla Girls in the early days took the form of protest, by wearing their gorilla masks and conducting \"weenie counts\" in museums, where the members would count he male to female work and subject ratios. Most notably in 1989 they found that The Met's public collections only had 5% of their works produced by women, while 85% of the works including nudity focused on a nude female. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref>\n\nThe Guerrilla Girls have been met with criticism and backlash. While they focus on the issue of diversity, it has been said that the majority of the members are white. Former member, Alma Thomas have noted the lack of effort in understanding the challenges faced by artists of color by other members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-guerrilla-girls-zora-neale-hurston-and-agnes-martin-15840|title=Oral history interview with Guerrilla Girls Zora Neale Hurston and Agnes Martin, 2008 May 17|website=www.aaa.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The Guerrilla Girls have also been accused of \u201cselling out,\u201d having their works shown at the same hegemonic establishments that they protested in the past.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/guerrilla-girl-power-have-americas-feminist-artists-sold-out-1666140.html|title=Guerrilla girl power: Have America's feminist artists sold out?|date=2009-04-09|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== [[Ana Mendieta]] ==\n\n=== Overview ===\nMendieta's work was greatly informed by the part of her identity that was embedded in the term \"immigrant\". She's widely known for her performance art piece and exhibition ''Traces''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-in-america/interviews/the-untold-ana-mendieta-56344/|title=The Untold: Ana Mendieta|last=Donnelly|first=Ryann|last2=Donnelly|first2=Ryann|date=2013-10-08|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>''.'' Her immigration from Cuba to the USA was full of displacement and separation from her homeland and many of her family members for a long period of time. This inspired her future work to explore the aspects of belonging, estrangement, feminism, life, death, violence and overall the rawness of the natural of femininity and the earth. Her fascinations with natures elements: water, fire, earth, air and the flesh were interwoven into her performance art work. She was a huge part of the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/body-art/ body art movement] which was it's own form that grew as a branch off from the trunk of performance art<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theartstory.org/artist/mendieta-ana/|title=Ana Mendieta Art, Bio, Ideas|website=The Art Story|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Furthermore, she was seen as a huge contributor to the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/earth-art/ land art movement] which she often paired with her body art to create her feminist and identity messages in her performance art pieces<ref name=\":3\" />. Her untimely death at 36 years old left audiences hurting for more, but some of her pieces still stand in art studios today such as [[Alison Jacques Gallery]] and are incorporated in conversations about feminist and immigrant artwork<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alisonjacquesgallery.com/exhibitions/|title=Gallery Programme|website=Alison Jacques Gallery|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>.  \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Feminist art]]\n", "text_old": "{{essay-like|date=November 2017}}\nAccording to scholar Virginia Mackenny, [[performance art]] is a great tool to mold and remold gender because performance art, in most instances, includes a direct subversion to everyday conventions. MacKenny also writes that feminist performance Art had a large presence \u201cin the late '60s and early '70s in America when, in the climate of protest constituted by the civil rights movement and [[second wave feminism]].\" There are several movements that fall under the category of feminist performance art, including Feminist Postmodernism, which took place during 1960-1970 and focused on the exploitation of women's bodies as a means for profit. Similarly, the Chicanx movement emerged in East Los Angeles during the 1970s, and focused on the Vietnam war, which was considered a post-apartheid movement.<ref name=\"MacKenny\">{{cite journal|last1=MacKenny|first1=Virginia|title=Post - Apartheid Performance Art as a Site of Gender Resistance|journal=Agenda Empowering Women for Gender Equity|date=2001|volume=49|pages=15\u201324|issn=1013-0950}}</ref>\n\n== Feminist Postmodernism ==\nAs Forte writes in her analysis of feminist performance art in the 1960s and 1970s, \u201cWithin this movement, women's performance emerges as a specific strategy that allies [[postmodernism]] and [[feminism]] \u2026 women used performance as a deconstructive strategy to demonstrate the objectification of women and its results\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Forte|first1=Jeanie|title=Women's Performance Art: Feminism and Postmodernism|journal=Theatre Journal|date=1988|volume=40.2|issn=0192-2882}}</ref> Another strategy that was commonly used by feminist performance artists during the postmodernist movement was \u201cremoving of the mask,\u201d which was utilized to demonstrate the consequences of female representations in the media, on the psyche of women. MacKenny also writes about the removing of the mask within Feminist Postmodernism. She writes, \u201cThis 'masquerade' or 'masking' occurs when women play with their assigned gender roles in multiple, often contradictory ways - adopting, adapting, overlaying and subverting the hegemonic discourse in the process.\u201d\n\n== Chicanx Movement ==\nDuring the late 1960s and early 1970s in East Los Angeles, protests broke out against the [[Vietnam War]] and its disproportionate death rate of 22% Chicanx people, while the percentage of the population that Chicanx people made up only 5% of the United States entire population.\n[[Asco (art collective)]], based in [[East Los Angeles, California|East LA]] commented on the impacts of the war on [[queer]] and brown identities, as well as the tragedies that occurred in the protests discussed above due to [[police brutality]]. The collective created visual and performative art. Some of their most famous performances experiment with gender roles, for example, one male identifying artist attended a club wearing \u201cbooty shorts, pink platforms, and a shirt that said \u2018just turned 21.\u2019\u201d<ref>{{cite book|last1=Perez|first1=Laura E.|title=Chicana art: the politics of spiritual and aesthetic altarities|date=2007|publisher=Durham: Duke U|isbn=978-0-8223-8988-0|doi=10.1215/9780822389880}}</ref>\nThe group continued to make performance and visual art that engaged with concepts related to queer and [[ethnic identity]] in East LA. During this period, East LA was ghettoized through a border of highways and dilapidated conditions.\n\n== Post Apartheid Movement ==\nMacKenny writes about two of the major players in the Post [[Apartheid]] performance art movement in [[South Africa]]. She first writes about Carol Anne Gainer and her performance entitled 'Exposed.' MacKenny explains that Gainer disrupts and subverts the binary as she performs as both the model and artist in this performance, which works to blur the \"distinction between artist/art, artist/model, constructor/constructed, finder/found, mind/body, subject/object.\"\nThe second artist which Mackenny writes about is a [[mixed race]] artist who performs a piece called 'Span.' MacKenny asserts that the artist Tracey Rose, alludes to Western societies exploitation of people of colour in scientific study and analysis, and the \"dissection and embalming of body parts of native 'others' (the most pertinent to the South African context being Saartje Baartman, a young Khoisan woman displayed for her unique genitalia and steatopygia, or enlarged buttocks),\" through her own display of her body.<ref name=\"MacKenny\"/> Her performance exposes her naked body and is contrasted against images of \"scientific\" exploitation, which both highlights the dichotomy between these subjects and engages with Mackenny's definition of post-apartheid performance art and its political aim to blur and disrupt binary structures.\n\n=== Anti War Performance Art Movement ===\nThe sociologist Rachel V Kutz-Flamenbaum writes about two major players in the anti-war performance art movement during the George W Bush administration. Code Pink, and Raging Grannies challenge and subvert gender norms in their performances, and thus, use very similar tactics and strategies. For instance, in Code Pink, Kutz-Flamenbaum asserts that, \"the emphasis on women\u2019s role as pacifist caregivers presents a nonthreatening image of women activists.\" \n\nThe perpetuated concept of women as non threatening, relies on the audiences association of pink as a non threatening and feminized colour. Kutz-Flamenbaum argues that \"Code Pink\u2019s use of civil disobedience and aggressive trailing of public officials confound and challenge normative gender expectations of women as passive, polite, and well-behaved.\"(95)<ref name=\"Kutz-Flamenbaum\">{{cite journal|last1=Kutz-Flamenbaum|first1=Rachel V|title=Code Pink, Raging Grannies, and the Missile Dick Chicks: Feminist Performance Activism in the Contemporary Anti-War Movement|journal=NWSA Journal|date=Spring 2001|volume=19|issue=1|pages=90\u201396|issn=1040-0656}}</ref>\nKutz-Flamenbaum claims that [[Raging Grannies]] similarly use this tactic in the description of their mission statement. Kutz-Flamenbaum explains that their mission statement \"illustrates the way Raging Grannies use norm- embracing stereotypes of 'little old ladies' and 'grannies' to challenge the gendered assumptions of their audiences.\" Their conscious performance as non-threatening and nurturing women, strategically and tactfully confront issues related to war and challenge the participation of the George W Bush administration in the war. \n\n== Performance Artists ==\n\n==[[Yoko Ono]]==\n\n=== Overview ===\nOno belonged to a generation of early feminist performance artists but is unique among them for her international fame as [[John Lennon]]\u2019s wife in the late 60s and 70s.  During their courtship the couple manipulated the press attention directed on them by documenting their relationship through performance art.<ref name=\":0\">Elizabeth Ann Lindau. \u201cMother Superior\u201d: Maternity and Creativity in the Work of Yoko Ono.\" ''Women and Music: A Journal of Gender and Culture'' 20 (University of Nebraska Press: 2016), 64.</ref> As Ono stated in a 1986 TV interview, \u201cwe were always together\u2026 we exchanged very fully between ourselves.\u201d<ref name=\":1\">''Yoko Ono on John Lennon's Assasination, Their Son Sean and Influencing The Beatles Breakup.'', ''YouTube'' (YouTube, 2017), <nowiki>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Suj8MCysBKQ</nowiki>)</ref> They emphasized this unusual situation, where the husband and wife worked together rather than the pair working separately outside the home, through their performance art \u201cBed-ins.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs an interracial couple they also challenged racial stereotypes. She confessed, \u201cI think it was a big lesson for the world that we were together\u2026 And I think it might have helped too for people to understand what it means to confront the interracial couple.\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nParenthood is a factor in the controversy surrounding Ono. Women were not usually part of performance art or rock music, and mothers in particular were antithetical to everything rock stood for. The public idea of rock music as youthful male rebellion placed mothers as the opponent. When Ono and Lennon began their relationship, Beatles fans saw this female influence as an intrusion and the force that broke up their favorite band. However, as Ono saw it, the [[The Beatles|Beatles]] grew apart naturally and she was not the primary cause.<ref name=\":1\" /> Public confusion was exacerbated with Ono\u2019s pregnancy. While pregnant with their son Sean, Ono announced to Lennon: \u201cI am carrying the baby nine months and that is enough. You take care of it afterwards.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> After Sean\u2019s birth, she ran the couple\u2019s business while Lennon stayed home as \u201chousehusband.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> Ono\u2019s hands off approach to parenting is a source of controversy because she was simultaneously too motherly and not motherly enough.\n\n=== Work ===\nOne of her early works is [[Cut Piece]], first performed in 1964 at the Yamaichi Concert Hall in Kyoto. She kneeled on the stage in her best suit and invited audience members to use scissors to cut it off of her. Confronting issues of gender, class and cultural identity, Ono sat silently until the piece concluded at her discretion.<ref>Munroe, Alexandra; Ono, Yoko; Hendricks, Jon; Altshuler, Bruce; Ross, David A.; Wenner, Jann S.; Concannon, Kevin C.; Tomii, Reiko; Sayle, Murray; Gomez, Edward M. (October 2000). Yes Yoko Ono. New York: Harry N. Abrams. {{ISBN|0-81094-587-8}}.</ref> Ono also published a book of conceptual art in 1964, entitled [[Grapefruit (book)|Grapefruit]]. The book reads like an instruction manual for the reader to create their own versions of her pieces either physically or in the imagination. Over the nearly 60 years that she has been active, Ono has created installations of modern art across the globe, recorded numerous original songs both with John Lennon and the [[Plastic Ono Band]], as well as individually, and continues in activism to this day.\n\n== Orlan==\nORLAN (born as Mireille Suzanne Francette Porte) is French performance artist, most known for her radical use of plastic surgery to form her work. She uses her face and body as a malleable tool to change her appearance and therefore change her art. She primarily used plastic surgery to morph and change her body in her theatrical expression. Orlan uses her body at the heart of her expression, to articulate her political, social and cultural beliefs. Due to suffering an ectopic pregnancy, she felt her body was changed dramatically, and through that, she chose to turn her body into artwork through the use of plastic surgery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/orlan/|title=ORLAN {{!}} artnet|website=www.artnet.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOne of her most notable performances was that of the 1977 International Contemporary Art Fair in Paris. On her exterior, she had a large photo of a torso on her chest. This was turned into a slot machine, where the audience could put a coin down the slot and watch it descend into the groin. As a reward, that audience member were given a kiss. She also displayed her sexual organs during menstruation under a magnifying glass for respective audience members to study. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Donger|first=Simon|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XoXFBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=orlan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyw_Da7snoAhVxlFwKHZmmAdsQ6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=orlan&f=false|title=ORLAN: A Hybrid Body of Artworks|last2=Shepherd|first2=Simon|date=2010-05-20|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-97128-0|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Bj\u00f6rk Gu\u00f0mundsd\u00f3ttir ==\nThe musical artist Bj\u00f6rk has been challenging musical barriers since her time in the band [[The Sugarcubes]], which became the biggest alternative rock band in Iceland. She has since gone on to a solo career, starting in 1993 with the album [[Debut (Bj\u00f6rk album)|''Debut'']] with her last album having been released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/bj%C3%B6rk-mn0000769444/biography|title=Bj\u00f6rk {{!}} Biography & History|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> She throughout her time has used her music to speak on matters she deemed important while following a unique and individualistic style for each of her albums. She finds something that she finds challenging or that she dislikes and work with it to create something she's proud of, allowing her to continue having these unique albums.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/4143741-interview--bjork-talks-piracy-punk-lady-gaga-and-biophilia|title=Interview: Bjork talks piracy, punk, Lady Gaga and Biophilia|last=October 9th|first=Kevin EG Perry|last2=2011|website=DrownedInSound|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== ''Biophilia and Environmental Work'' ===\nThis has lead to one of her most famous albums ''[[Biophilia (album)|Biophilia]]'' which was Bj\u00f6rk's two year long passion project to give her music a more visual and hands on feel. The album was developed into an iPad and iPod app that allowed users to listen to each song while playing games that visually showcased the music. The most notable example is the song \u2018Thunderbolt\u2019  which allows listeners to draw \"Tesla coil charges which alter the bass lines you hear\" and when she performs the song live she has twin Tesla coils to play the bass line.<ref name=\":2\" /> This album however was more than a challenge for Bj\u00f6rk to create a new sound, she created the album as a response to the environmental issues Iceland was facing in 2008. Iceland had allowed the aluminum smelters to take over the countries fishing industry while being the cause for excessive greenhouse gas emissions. Her goal was to create an album that could educate people about the world we are living in and inspire them to take actions against companies that work to destroy the planet.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/07/bjork-environmental-campaign-timetable-nordic-schools|title=Bj\u00f6rk's environmental campaign goes on the timetable in Nordic schools|date=2014-06-07|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-04-03|last2=arts|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|last3=correspondent|first3=media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/11/13/bjork-wages-battle-against-icelandic-aluminum/|title=Bj\u00f6rk Wages Battle Against Icelandic Aluminum|last=Kanter|first=James|date=2008-11-13|website=Green Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n=== 'Declare Independence' and Activism ===\nThis environmental work would not be the only time she has used her music and voice to speak out as the song 'Declare Independence' would often be a song she would use to speak out for the freedom of nations trying to seceded from the nations they have been forced to be apart of. Most notable was when she, unauthorized, sang the song in her Shanghai concert in 2008, chanting Tibet in the middle of the song.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7276891.stm|title=Bjork makes 'free Tibet' gesture|date=2008-03-04|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> At the time Tibet was revolting against China for its freedom, and as such her use of the song caused many concert goers to leave the venue and the Chinese government to tighten their regulations for all outside performers from then on. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7293605.stm|title=Western acts 'welcome' in China|date=2008-03-13|access-date=2020-04-03|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Lady Gaga ==\nLady Gaga (Stefani Joanne Angelina Germanotta) has experimented and incorporated performance art into her life. Her first internet appearance in performance art came in 2013 in a kickstarter for \u201cThe Abromovic Method\u201d ran by Marina Abromovic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/71937056|title=The Abramovic Method Practiced by Lady Gaga|website=Vimeo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>This video was taken during a physical and spiritual retreat she participated that was hosted by Abromovic at her summer home. Gaga is featured \u201cfilling the room\u201d with her voice and wandering naked in the woods. Gaga was asked to test her body and go through strenuous activities. She also added to the piece by participating fully and even suggesting additions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://culturacolectiva.com/art/lady-gaga-marina-abramovic-collaboration|title=The Day Lady Gaga Stripped To Please Marina Abramovic and Be Free From Drugs|date=2017-01-30|website=culturacolectiva.com|language=English|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Abbromovic reported she was a very compliant student. Later, Gaga fit performance art into her 2011 Video Music Awards appearance. She showed up to perform her song \u201cYou and I\u201d dressed up as a person deemed Jo Calderone. <ref>{{Citation|title=Jo Calderone (Lady Gaga) You And I Live - VMAs 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SkWoA25V4tQ|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> When speaking, she spoke with a Brooklyn accent and walk, and spoke as a typical man. She commented that performance art meant fully committing and diving into a character including, acting as the character the whole night. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1669957/lady-gaga-jo-calderone-vmas/|title=Why Did Lady Gaga Go To VMAs As Jo Calderone?|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>They finished their speech at the award show talking about the importance of accepting people for who they are with no discrimination, because it was they way they were born.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/lady-gaga-339-1286022|title=Lady Gaga performs as male alter ego Jo Calderone at MTV VMAs {{!}} NME|date=2011-08-29|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Later Gaga dabbled with the performance art of \u201cCamp\u201d at the 2019 Met Gala. \"Camp\" is a form of performance art through clothing that stems from the drag culture and is meant to tell a story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://depauliaonline.com/41447/artslife/camp-the-theme-that-means-the-most-or-nothing-at-all/|title=Camp: the theme that means the most \u2013 or nothing at all|last=Oxnevad|first=Emma|date=2019-05-13|website=The DePaulia|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance through clothing ====\nHer outfit for the Met Gala consisted of four overlapping outfits that she stripped from one to the next while on the red carpet for the Gala.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Peters|first=Micheal A|date=January 2012|title=On the Edge of Theory: Lady Gaga, performance and cultural theory|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwVV3NCsIwDC6yg7_vEPAkOLGuW1tvIv6B4EW9jmzddlNxevDtTdyGeuolCaVNkyZNvnaFR3Fr1hKdmYy48yOcefywq_hcBbrd5D8YZ0YF045YHC5Adx3g9BFcc_g08L3msEf3gg0WOIbbt4YeKL6GBpSipu0L73F_ZoNq6InTenVcbv36MwG_YFAqPzQJ6Sqiy6RLlMxDY8n1WtQBzVBl1jolU0PeNpeJY5ASIjaJZguvXW74Y91hJbcx2XG92-UHZNNMtY0YfHBSUbF9j1lJHndMsa51p4VhuKV4wWIVO1NiGP0xcIU6meUCn2UZ7w7nX9o339xjrg|journal=Contemporary readings in Law and social Justice|volume=4|pages=1|via=}}</ref> The outfits consisted of black and pink and had a coy, classic femme aesthetic.She also had a team providing her with props like a suitcase, wagon and 90\u2019s telephone. She also represented performance art on a mainstream platform with two separate VMA appearances. One was in 2010, when she wore a \u201cmeat dress\u201d to the show. The dress consisted of prime rib and flank steak. The dress was referencing a speech \u201cThe Prime Rib of America\u201d, that encouraged the end of discrimination against gay men and women in the military and Gaga stated the military denies them \u201c the greatest cut of meat my country has to offer.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/lady-gaga-meat-dress-explanation|title=Getting Political|website=British Vogue|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> The second was the Joe Calerone one previously mentioned, both performed with intent of raising awareness to a cause.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kumari|first=Ashanka|date=April 2016|title=\"You and I\"|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMw42JgAfZbUxkgJ4GCF80UJJfqAasRA1Mm0NmlJga6ppbGwDwEPcUb2MPggBWdwNaEASdDwKOGOZH5h_coAPvSCp6PGuZaKUB3rVaChYAtI4UAxLJ6hfw0heDUnDSFzDwFn8SUSgX3xPREsELwJpDkwyt5GFhKikpTeSEUN0Oom2uIs4cu9LYBXVCVZ6prngwszFMNLcyTjdIsDI2TzE2SUlIsLU2NUkySk43NTYEJNTHVJDUl0SQ5CbQdNBlYV6aapYAyhWliYhro4nUtiLmw-i2-AHJgRDy8oQ0MiXhwSAAVq0IVo0x2xyeCphvig4ANKVDWAF2iZAhRB2454zEx3ivAORRiNgDmtXCK|journal=The Journal of Pop Culture|volume=49|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== Performance of her own feminism ====\nShe preaches about equality to all through the removing of labels and just treating people as people. Her main message is to spread kindness over all else.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jennex|first=Craig|date=July 2013|title=Diva Worship and the Sonic Search for Queer Utopia|url=https://ucblibraries.summon.serialssolutions.com/#!/search?ho=t&l=en&bookMark=ePnHCXMwfV09DwIhDCXmBj__A4sjBo7qweTgR1z9uDgSUEicNOb090vhjLo4sRRIF9pH2_f6pIi41ZN2Sg1prGXijMF-ACEnlVZTgE4aU-RMVKIs0j8_Z2jT_TyiHHqkXF6elh6vqaOXRmhNY1ZE90gaS3M7Lo2pHd1GzHendXO9XeyQFM394Ud5GZB6vTosNqxVFmAnyRWwADNnBaCanXBVlVjDtJKOSzs7O-twHFW7ABq8kFaBdlB6OPMgrPcyoMg65HPfsczcMjmEEW_OzdZrg16b7HXcNm63_ZS4jcUig9nFbD3Gb4V282z3zZ5qmoThQxbcMPLvTS-VRmpL|journal=Popular Music and Society: Fandom|volume=36|pages=3|via=}}</ref> She believes women have the right to choose the life they see fit for themselves, even if it means dependent on others. She is also a big advocate for sexual assault awareness as she is a survivor herself. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Corona|first=Victor P.|date=2013|title=Memory, Monsters, and Lady Gaga|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|journal=The Journal of Popular Culture|language=en|volume=46|issue=4|pages=725\u2013744|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5931.2011.00809.x|issn=1540-5931}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== The Guerrilla Girls ==\nThe Guerrilla Girls formed in New York City in the mid 1980s.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/guerrilla-girls-6858|title=Guerrilla Girls|last=Tate|website=Tate|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>The Guerrilla Girls focused their performances, protests, installations, and exhibits on highlighting the lack of representation of women and people of color within the art world.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> Most notably, The Guerrilla Girls donned gorilla masks and costumes during protest in order to maintain anonymity, and to make their work more about the issues rather than each member\u2019s own identity.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nAfter protesting the lack of diversity at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City in 1985, the Guerrilla Girls expanded their work into prints, billboards, public commissions, and, indoor exhibitions. This also came with their work focusing on a wider array of issues such as the wage gap, tokenism, and funding for the arts.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref> The public performances of the Guerrilla Girls in the early days took the form of protest, by wearing their gorilla masks and conducting \"weenie counts\" in museums, where the members would count he male to female work and subject ratios. Most notably in 1989 they found that The Met's public collections only had 5% of their works produced by women, while 85% of the works including nudity focused on a nude female. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Gerber|first=Courtney|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/gao/9781884446054.article.t2021709|title=Guerrilla Girls|date=2006-09-20|publisher=Oxford University Press|series=Oxford Art Online}}</ref>\n\nThe Guerrilla Girls have been met with criticism and backlash. While they focus on the issue of diversity, it has been said that the majority of the members are white. Former member, Alma Thomas have noted the lack of effort in understanding the challenges faced by artists of color by other members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-guerrilla-girls-zora-neale-hurston-and-agnes-martin-15840|title=Oral history interview with Guerrilla Girls Zora Neale Hurston and Agnes Martin, 2008 May 17|website=www.aaa.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> The Guerrilla Girls have also been accused of \u201cselling out,\u201d having their works shown at the same hegemonic establishments that they protested in the past.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/guerrilla-girl-power-have-americas-feminist-artists-sold-out-1666140.html|title=Guerrilla girl power: Have America's feminist artists sold out?|date=2009-04-09|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== [[Ana Mendieta|Anna Mendieta]] ==\n\n=== Overview ===\nMendieta's work was greatly informed by the part of her identity that was embedded in the term \"immigrant\". She's widely known for her performance art piece and exhibition ''Traces''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artnews.com/art-in-america/interviews/the-untold-ana-mendieta-56344/|title=The Untold: Ana Mendieta|last=Donnelly|first=Ryann|last2=Donnelly|first2=Ryann|date=2013-10-08|website=ARTnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>''.'' Her immigration from Cuba to the USA was full of displacement and separation from her homeland and many of her family members for a long period of time. This inspired her future work to explore the aspects of belonging, estrangement, feminism, life, death, violence and overall the rawness of the natural of femininity and the earth. Her fascinations with natures elements: water, fire, earth, air and the flesh were interwoven into her performance art work. She was a huge part of the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/body-art/ body art movement] which was it's own form that grew as a branch off from the trunk of performance art<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theartstory.org/artist/mendieta-ana/|title=Ana Mendieta Art, Bio, Ideas|website=The Art Story|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. Furthermore, she was seen as a huge contributor to the [https://www.theartstory.org/movement/earth-art/ land art movement] which she often paired with her body art to create her feminist and identity messages in her performance art pieces<ref name=\":3\" />. Her untimely death at 36 years old left audiences hurting for more, but some of her pieces still stand in art studios today such as [[Alison Jacques Gallery]] and are incorporated in conversations about feminist and immigrant artwork<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alisonjacquesgallery.com/exhibitions/|title=Gallery Programme|website=Alison Jacques Gallery|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>.  \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Feminist art]]\n", "name_user": "SibLion", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnna Mendieta", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feminist_performance_art"}
{"title_page": "Croupier", "text_new": "{{short description|Someone appointed at a gambling table to assist in the conduct of the game}}\n{{for|the 1998 film starring Clive Owen|Croupier (film)}}\n[[Image:Croupier de Hold'em Poker.jpg|thumb|A croupier deals cards for a game of [[Texas hold 'em]]]]\nA '''croupier''' or '''dealer''' is someone appointed at a [[gambling]] table to assist in the conduct of the game, especially in the distribution of bets and payouts. Croupiers are typically employed by [[casino]]s.\n\nIn macao, it is a high salary job that don't need brain. Attract millions of nmslese.\n\n==Origin of the word==\nOriginally a \"croupier\" meant one who stood behind a gambler, with extra reserves of cash to back him up during a gambling session. The word derived from ''croupe'' (the [[rump (animal)|rump]] of a horse) and was by way of analogy to one who rode behind on horseback. It later came to refer to one who was employed to collect the money from a gaming-table.<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary]], ''Croupier''</ref>\n\nOriginally a \"dealer\" meant one who was responsible for distributing cards or the player in the dealer position, regardless of whether or not that player was responsible for distributing the cards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.pokerzone.com/dealer|title=Definition of Dealer - PokerZone|website=dictionary.pokerzone.com}}</ref>\n\n== Training ==\n[[File:Gambling games 4.jpg|thumb|A blackjack dealer at [[Harrah's Las Vegas]]]]\nTraining methods to become a casino croupier vary from country to country. In North America, [[blackjack]] is almost always the game that dealers learn first, as it is simple and popular, and when the dealer makes errors, they tend not to cost the casino much money. In Europe, croupiers tend to learn [[roulette]] first. Complex, busy games such as [[craps]], with complicated payout systems, etc., are usually reserved for the most competent and/or ambitious dealers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jobboomcc.canoe.ca/News/2005/10/19/1269228-sun.html|title=Career advice - Job tips for workers and job seekers - Jobboom -|website=Career advice - Job tips for workers and job seekers - Jobboom}}</ref>\n\nSelect colleges and non-collegiate third-level educational institutions now offer croupier training courses, formally dubbed Casino Operations Training, which when put it in an historical context is a milestone achievement for the legitimization of poker in the mainstream. Besides courses, there's a host of private lessons available on social media, poker forums and classifieds sections worldwide, which could serve even better than attending an official course, giving one-on-one apprentice\u2013master attention.\n\nCasinos may also offer an in-house training program. However, sometimes it serves better to get a \"general qualification\" than to be trained exclusively into one companies way of operating. Prospective employers often prefer candidates without fully relevant experience over a candidate highly experienced in the idiosyncrasies of another operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ggpoker.com/how-to-become-a-casino-croupier/|title=How to become a Croupier|date=2019-07-03|website=GGPoker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== Licensing ==\n[[United States|American]], [[Australia]]n, [[Canada|Canadian]] and [[United Kingdom|British]] croupiers are required to apply for a gambling license. This license includes police background checks and credit rating checks, to help determine if they are eligible to commence employment. Croupiers are not permitted to deal at a casino until being issued this license.\n\n== Tipping ==\nAs is common with customer service staff in the United States, croupiers there depend on tips to make their wage worthwhile. While a croupier should theoretically have no personal interest in the outcome of the game, a successful player customarily tips the croupier, especially in American casinos. Tips are often pooled and divided amongst all the staff. Fraternising with customers is frowned upon, and most casinos prevent their gambling staff from being seen smoking or even being seen in uniform outside the casino. Some gambling strategies include suggestions to tip the casino dealer in order to create a good atmosphere and improve dealer's mood. According to these strategies, tipping might even make the dealer shuffle the cards less frequently and thereby allow easier tracking of particular cards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://casinoobserver.com/casino-news-item-article-ground-casino-rules.htm|title=Land Casino rules |publisher=casinoobserver.com |accessdate=2010-09-25}}</ref> Australian casinos forbid dealers from taking tips.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star.com.au|title=Casino|accessdate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Secondhand smoke exposure==\nBecause casinos tend to allow smoking on the gambling floor, American croupiers are exposed to [[secondhand smoke]]. A [[Health Hazard Evaluation Program|health hazard evaluation]] of several [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]] casinos showed that nonsmoker croupiers suffered from more respiratory ailments than their administrative counterparts at the casinos and had [[cotinine]] and [[NNAL]] (both components of secondhand smoke) in their urine samples.<ref>West, Christine. [https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/blog/nsb061609_casino.html Secondhand Smoke and Casino Dealers]. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health. June 16, 2009.</ref> [[United Kingdom|Britain]] banned smoking in all public places, including casinos, in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/4375478.stm|title=Smoke ban bill details released|date=27 October 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Poker dealer]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n*[http://www.cardplayer.com/poker-news/7160-wsop-a-day-in-the-life-of-a-dealer Card Player magazine Day in the life story]\n\n[[Category:Personal care and service occupations]]\n[[Category:Gambling terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Someone appointed at a gambling table to assist in the conduct of the game}}\n{{for|the 1998 film starring Clive Owen|Croupier (film)}}\n[[Image:Croupier de Hold'em Poker.jpg|thumb|A croupier deals cards for a game of [[Texas hold 'em]]]]\nA '''croupier''' or '''dealer''' is someone appointed at a [[gambling]] table to assist in the conduct of the game, especially in the distribution of bets and payouts. Croupiers are typically employed by [[casino]]s.\n\n==Origin of the word==\nOriginally a \"croupier\" meant one who stood behind a gambler, with extra reserves of cash to back him up during a gambling session. The word derived from ''croupe'' (the [[rump (animal)|rump]] of a horse) and was by way of analogy to one who rode behind on horseback. It later came to refer to one who was employed to collect the money from a gaming-table.<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary]], ''Croupier''</ref>\n\nOriginally a \"dealer\" meant one who was responsible for distributing cards or the player in the dealer position, regardless of whether or not that player was responsible for distributing the cards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.pokerzone.com/dealer|title=Definition of Dealer - PokerZone|website=dictionary.pokerzone.com}}</ref>\n\n== Training ==\n[[File:Gambling games 4.jpg|thumb|A blackjack dealer at [[Harrah's Las Vegas]]]]\nTraining methods to become a casino croupier vary from country to country. In North America, [[blackjack]] is almost always the game that dealers learn first, as it is simple and popular, and when the dealer makes errors, they tend not to cost the casino much money. In Europe, croupiers tend to learn [[roulette]] first. Complex, busy games such as [[craps]], with complicated payout systems, etc., are usually reserved for the most competent and/or ambitious dealers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jobboomcc.canoe.ca/News/2005/10/19/1269228-sun.html|title=Career advice - Job tips for workers and job seekers - Jobboom -|website=Career advice - Job tips for workers and job seekers - Jobboom}}</ref>\n\nSelect colleges and non-collegiate third-level educational institutions now offer croupier training courses, formally dubbed Casino Operations Training, which when put it in an historical context is a milestone achievement for the legitimization of poker in the mainstream. Besides courses, there's a host of private lessons available on social media, poker forums and classifieds sections worldwide, which could serve even better than attending an official course, giving one-on-one apprentice\u2013master attention.\n\nCasinos may also offer an in-house training program. However, sometimes it serves better to get a \"general qualification\" than to be trained exclusively into one companies way of operating. Prospective employers often prefer candidates without fully relevant experience over a candidate highly experienced in the idiosyncrasies of another operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ggpoker.com/how-to-become-a-casino-croupier/|title=How to become a Croupier|date=2019-07-03|website=GGPoker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n== Licensing ==\n[[United States|American]], [[Australia]]n, [[Canada|Canadian]] and [[United Kingdom|British]] croupiers are required to apply for a gambling license. This license includes police background checks and credit rating checks, to help determine if they are eligible to commence employment. Croupiers are not permitted to deal at a casino until being issued this license.\n\n== Tipping ==\nAs is common with customer service staff in the United States, croupiers there depend on tips to make their wage worthwhile. While a croupier should theoretically have no personal interest in the outcome of the game, a successful player customarily tips the croupier, especially in American casinos. Tips are often pooled and divided amongst all the staff. Fraternising with customers is frowned upon, and most casinos prevent their gambling staff from being seen smoking or even being seen in uniform outside the casino. Some gambling strategies include suggestions to tip the casino dealer in order to create a good atmosphere and improve dealer's mood. According to these strategies, tipping might even make the dealer shuffle the cards less frequently and thereby allow easier tracking of particular cards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://casinoobserver.com/casino-news-item-article-ground-casino-rules.htm|title=Land Casino rules |publisher=casinoobserver.com |accessdate=2010-09-25}}</ref> Australian casinos forbid dealers from taking tips.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star.com.au|title=Casino|accessdate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Secondhand smoke exposure==\nBecause casinos tend to allow smoking on the gambling floor, American croupiers are exposed to [[secondhand smoke]]. A [[Health Hazard Evaluation Program|health hazard evaluation]] of several [[Las Vegas Strip|Las Vegas]] casinos showed that nonsmoker croupiers suffered from more respiratory ailments than their administrative counterparts at the casinos and had [[cotinine]] and [[NNAL]] (both components of secondhand smoke) in their urine samples.<ref>West, Christine. [https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/blog/nsb061609_casino.html Secondhand Smoke and Casino Dealers]. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health. June 16, 2009.</ref> [[United Kingdom|Britain]] banned smoking in all public places, including casinos, in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/4375478.stm|title=Smoke ban bill details released|date=27 October 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Poker dealer]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n*[http://www.cardplayer.com/poker-news/7160-wsop-a-day-in-the-life-of-a-dealer Card Player magazine Day in the life story]\n\n[[Category:Personal care and service occupations]]\n[[Category:Gambling terminology]]\n", "name_user": "60.246.101.18", "label": "un