our high burj. The defence strategy of the fort is example of architectural skills of the Gohad Jat rulers. <ref>Ranvir Singh:, \"Utila Garhi\", Jat-Veer Smarika, Gwalior, 1992, p. 45</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{MadhyaPradesh-geo-stub}}\n\n\n[[Category:Villages in Gwalior district]]\n[[Category:Forts in Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "Premeditated Chaos", "label": "safe", "comment": "+navbox (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utila_Fort"}
{"title_page": "Yesterday (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Danny Boyle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| image          = Yesterday (2019 poster).png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Danny Boyle]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tim Bevan]]\n* [[Eric Fellner]]\n* Bernie Bellew\n* Matthew James Wilkinson\n* [[Richard Curtis]]\n* Danny Boyle\n}}\n| screenplay     = Richard Curtis\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Jack Barth\n* Richard Curtis\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Himesh Patel]]\n* [[Lily James]]\n* [[Ed Sheeran]]\n* [[Kate McKinnon]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Daniel Pemberton]]\n| cinematography = Christopher Ross\n| editing        = [[Jon Harris (director)|Jon Harris]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Perfect World Pictures]]\n* [[Working Title Films]]\n* Decibel Films\n* [[Dentsu Inc.]]<ref name=\"BFI\">{{cite web |title=Yesterday (2019) |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5ce28fc0a979f |website=BFI |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2019|5|4|[[Tribeca Film Festival|Tribeca]]|2019|06|28|United Kingdom & United States}}\n| country        = {{unbulleted list|United Kingdom|United States|China|Japan<ref name=\"BFI\"/>}}\n| runtime        = 116 minutes\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $26 million<ref name=\"BOM\" />\n| gross          = {{US$|153.7 million|long=no}}<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=untitleddannyboyle.htm |title=Yesterday (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Yesterday''''' is a 2019 [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Danny Boyle]] and screenplay by [[Richard Curtis]], based on a story by Jack Barth and Curtis.<ref name=\"ItzkoffNYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/movies/yesterday-movie-beatles-songs.html |title=The Long and Winding Road to 'Yesterday,' a Film Full of Beatles Music |last1=Itzkoff |first1=Dave |date=June 28, 2019 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.screendaily.com/features/the-story-behind-beatles-film-yesterday-richard-curtis-danny-boyle-working-title-and-a-rising-uk-producer/5138875.article |title=The story behind Beatles film 'Yesterday': Richard Curtis, Danny Boyle, Working Title and a rising UK producer |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |date=3 May 2019 |website=[[Screen Daily]] |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> The film, named after [[Yesterday (Beatles song)|the song of the same name]] written by [[John Lennon]] and [[Paul McCartney]], stars [[Himesh Patel]] as a struggling musician Jack Malik, who, after an accident, finds himself the only person who remembers [[The Beatles]] and becomes famous after taking credit for their songs. The film also stars [[Lily James]] as the protagonist's childhood friend and love interest, [[Kate McKinnon]] as his obnoxious manager, and [[Ed Sheeran]] as a fictionalised version of himself.\n\nThe project was announced in March 2018. Filming began the following month around England, particularly [[Norfolk]] and Halesworth in Suffolk. Photography also took place at [[Wembley Stadium]], [[Millennium Stadium|Principality Stadium]] and in [[Los Angeles]]. The filmmakers paid $10 million for the rights to use [[The Beatles discography|the Beatles' music]]; although none of the members were involved, Boyle received approval for the project from them and their families.\n\n''Yesterday'' had its world premiere at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] on 4 May 2019,<ref name=\"2019-03-14 Variety\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/tribeca-danny-boyle-yesterday-closing-night-film-1203162974/ |title=Danny Boyle's Beatles Movie 'Yesterday' Selected as Tribeca Closing Night Film |last1=McNary |first1=Dave |date=14 March 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |issn=0042-2738 |oclc=810134503 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331031320/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/tribeca-danny-boyle-yesterday-closing-night-film-1203162974/ |archive-date=31 March 2019}}</ref> and was released in the United Kingdom and the United States on 28 June 2019, by [[Universal Pictures]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/danny-boyles-lily-james-kate-mckinnon-comedy-lands-fall-2019-release-1103183 |title=Danny Boyle's Lily James-Kate McKinnon Comedy Lands Fall 2019 Release |first=Pamela |last=McClintock |date=16 April 2018 |newspaper=[[Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> The film grossed $153 million worldwide against a production budget of $26 million. It received mixed reviews from critics, with praise for the premise, performances, and [[musical film|musical]] sequences, but criticism of the familiarity and not taking the concept further.\n\n==Plot==\nJack Malik is a struggling singer-songwriter from [[Lowestoft]]. His manager and childhood friend Ellie Appleton encourages him not to give up on his dreams. During a global blackout, Jack is hit by a bus. After recovering, he sings the [[the Beatles|Beatles]] song \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\" for his friends, and discovers they have never heard of the Beatles. After realising no one in the world remembers them, Jack begins performing Beatles songs, passing them off as his own.\n\nEllie has Jack record a demo with a local music producer, Gavin. While recording day and night in Gavin's recording room, Malik published and gave out his album to every customer he sees back at Lowestoft. Following a performance on local television, Jack is invited by pop star [[Ed Sheeran]] to play as his opening act in Moscow. Ellie declines to join him, saying she must work at her day job as a schoolteacher, so Jack's [[Road crew|roadie]] friend Rocky travels with him instead. After the gig, Sheeran challenges Jack to a songwriting duel; he loses to Jack's \"[[The Long and Winding Road]]\". In Los Angeles, Sheeran's ruthless manager Debra Hammer signs him to her label and engineers his rise to global fame.\n\nAt Jack's going-away party, Ellie confesses that she has always been in love with him. Jack goes back to Los Angeles and starts recording the album at [[EastWest Studios]], but cannot remember the lyrics for the song he was trying to \"write,\" \"[[Eleanor Rigby]].\" Hoping to trigger memories, Jack goes to the Beatles' hometown of [[Liverpool]], visiting landmarks such as [[Strawberry Field]], [[Penny Lane, Liverpool|Penny Lane]], and the grave of [[Eleanor Rigby#Real people named Eleanor Rigby|Eleanor Rigby]]. Ellie joins him in Liverpool, and they spend a drunken evening and kiss, but Ellie tells him she is not interested in a one-night stand. The next morning, Jack and Rocky pursue Ellie to the train station, where she congratulates Jack but tells him she cannot be a part of his celebrity life. Jack returns to Los Angeles, heartbroken; Ellie begins dating Gavin.\n\nThe record label prepares to launch Jack's debut album. The producers reject his suggested titles, taken from Beatles records, and name the album ''One Man Only'', pushing his talent. Jack persuades them to launch the album with a [[The Beatles' rooftop concert|rooftop concert]] in [[Gorleston-on-Sea]]. Backstage, two fans approach him and tell him they know he plagiarised the songs, but thank him, having feared the Beatles' music was gone forever. They give him the address of [[John Lennon]], who has survived into old age, out of the public spotlight. John, who has lived a happy life with his wife, advises Jack to pursue the one he loves and always tell the truth.\n\nSheeran arranges for Jack to perform at [[Wembley Stadium]]. Jack confesses to the crowd that he plagiarised the music and that he loves Ellie, and has Rocky upload the songs free to the internet, sabotaging the record release, much to Debra\u2019s anger, who is enraged over Jack\u2019s confession. \n\nEventually, Jack and Ellie marry and have a family together, and Jack becomes a music teacher. During the story Jack also discovers other things have disappeared, such as [[Coca-Cola]], [[cigarettes]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], and [[Harry Potter]].\n\n==Cast==\n<!--- Cast and order per tombstone closing credits, roles per closing credits scroll --->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Himesh Patel]] as Jack Malik\n* [[Lily James]] as Ellie Appleton\n* [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] as Rocky\n* [[Ed Sheeran]] as himself\n* [[Kate McKinnon]] as Debra Hammer\n* [[Sanjeev Bhaskar]] as Jed Malik\n* [[Meera Syal]] as Shelia Malik\n* Harry Michell as Nick\n* [[Sophia Di Martino]] as Carol\n* [[Sarah Lancashire]] as Liz (Liverpool stranger)\n* [[Alexander Arnold (actor)|Alexander Arnold]] as Gavin\n* [[Lamorne Morris]] as Head of Marketing\n}}\n\nIn addition, [[James Corden]] (hosting his show) and [[Michael Kiwanuka]] (waiting for Rocky to bring guitar) appear as themselves, [[Justin Edwards (actor)|Justin Edwards]] plays Leo (the Russian stranger who remembers the Beatles), and [[Robert Carlyle]] makes an uncredited appearance as [[John Lennon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/yesterday-movie-john-lennon-actor-robert-carlyle/ |title=Who Plays [SPOILER] In Yesterday? |first=John |last=Orquiola |date=28 June 2019 |work=[[Screen Rant]] |accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe film began as an original screenplay called ''Cover Version'', by writer Jack Barth and actor-writer-director [[Mackenzie Crook]], with Crook intending to direct the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-nowhere-man-behind-the-yesterday-script-11561392902? |title='Yesterday': The Real Story Behind The Beatles-Inspired Movie |last1=Watson |first1=R. T. |date=6 June 2019 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/inside-making-yesterday-beatles-ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-richard-curtis-846248/ |title=How 'Yesterday' Breathes New Life Into the Beatles' Music |last1=Browne |first1=David |date=25 June 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ItzkoffNYT\" /> A few years later, after Crook had dropped out due to other commitments, the story was pitched to writer-director [[Richard Curtis]], who loved the idea but wanted to write his own script for it. Whereas in ''Cover Version'', the lead character achieves only moderate success with the Beatles songs, Curtis's lead character becomes the world's most celebrated singer-songwriter. Curtis also shifted focus onto the love story between the male and female leads.\n\nIn March 2018, it was announced that director [[Danny Boyle]] and writer Richard Curtis were working together on a [[Musical comedy film|musical comedy]] that would be set in the 1960s or 1970s and centre on \"a struggling musician who thinks he's the only person who can remember [[The Beatles]]\" with [[Himesh Patel]] cast in the lead role.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/danny-boyle-richard-curtis-team-universal-comedy-1089881 |title=Danny Boyle, Richard Curtis Team for Universal Comedy |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=1 March 2018 |newspaper=[[Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> [[Ed Sheeran]]'s supporting role was originally intended for [[Chris Martin]], who turned it down.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/yesterday-ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-beatles-1202153594/ |title='Yesterday': Ed Sheeran's Smart Casting Advice Saved Danny Boyle's Beatles Rom-Com |last1=Thompson |first1=Anne |date=2 July 2019 |website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref> For the lead role, Patel was selected from the many actors who auditioned, with Boyle convinced Patel was the right choice after listening to him perform \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\" and \"[[Back in the U.S.S.R.]]\" during auditions.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/features/yesterday-movie-beatles-danny-boyle-interview-1203249029/ |title=Danny Boyle on 'Yesterday,' Leaving 'Bond 25' and Why the Beatles Still Rock |last1=Rubin |first1=Rebecca |date=25 June 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=2 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Boyle felt that Patel's voice had soul; Sheeran agreed.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> In addition to acting, the Beatles cover songs in the film are sung by Patel, who also plays the guitar and piano.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.classicfm.com/discover-music/does-himesh-patel-sing-play-guitar-yesterday-movie/ |title=Does Himesh Patel sing and play guitar in Yesterday the movie? |date=1 July 2019 |website=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] |accessdate=2 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\nLater in March 2018, [[Lily James]] and [[Kate McKinnon]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lily-james-talks-star-danny-boyle-comedy-1093179 |title=Lily James in Talks to Star in Danny Boyle Comedy (Exclusive) |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=8 March 2018 |newspaper=Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kate-mckinnon-talks-join-lily-james-danny-boyle-comedy-1098509 |title=Kate McKinnon in Talks to Join Lily James in Danny Boyle Comedy |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=30 March 2018 |newspaper=Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Boyle informed the surviving members and widows of the band about the film and received a reply he described as \"lovely\" from Beatles drummer [[Ringo Starr]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.picturehouses.com/blog/the-big-interview-danny-boyle |title=The Big Interview: Danny Boyle |first=James |last=Mottram |date=26 April 2019 |website=[[Picturehouse Cinemas|Picturehouse]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> In April 2018, it was revealed that Ed Sheeran had joined the cast and would potentially also write new music for the film, which would also include Beatles songs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/ed-sheeran-in-talks-for-danny-boyle-working-title-beatles-musical-1202364467/ |title=Ed Sheeran In Talks For Danny Boyle-Richard Curtis Music-Themed Comedy Movie |first=Andreas |last=Wiseman |date=15 April 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-musical-comedy-movie-beatles/ |title=Ed Sheeran in Talks to Join Danny Boyle's Beatles-Themed Musical Comedy |first=Adam |last=Chitwood |authorlink=Adam Chitwood |work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] | date=15 April 2018 |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> Later that month, [[Ana de Armas]] and [[Lamorne Morris]] had also joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/ana-de-armas-danny-boyle-untitled-romantic-comedy-universal-1202375910/ |title=Ana de Armas Makes A Date With Danny Boyle Untitled Romantic Comedy |first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |date=24 April 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/new-girl-lamorne-morris-danny-boyle-untitled-comedy-casting-1202378296/ |title='New Girl's Lamorne Morris Joins Universal's Danny Boyle-Richard Curtis Comedy |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=27 April 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> In May 2018, [[Sophia Di Martino]], [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] and Harry Michell joined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/danny-boyle-untitled-romantic-comedy-james-bond-casting-1202385464/ |title=Danny Boyle & Richard Curtis Untitled Romantic Comedy Adds Three |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=8 May 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nFilming began on 21 April 2018,<ref>{{cite tweet |first=Emma |last=Freud |user=emmafreud |number=987757367407333376 |title=We began shooting our new movie today |date=21 April 2018 |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> with production in the United Kingdom starting on 26 April 2018, with scenes filmed all around Suffolk in [[Cantley, Norfolk|Cantley]], [[Halesworth]], [[Dunwich]], [[Shingle Street]], [[Latitude Festival]] and [[Clacton-on-Sea]], [[Essex]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/16187446.Danny_Boyle_s_new_Beatles_musical_is_being_filmed_in_north_Essex/ |title=Danny Boyle's new Beatles musical was being filmed in north Essex |first=Chris |last=Wilkin |date=26 April 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Gazette (Colchester)|Daily Gazette]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> A casting call was issued for extras in overnight scenes shot immediately after Sheeran's four consecutive concerts at the [[Millennium Stadium|Principality Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]] in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/ed-sheeran-rumoured-danny-boyles-14535623 |title=Ed Sheeran is rumoured to be in Danny Boyle's new film |last=Bevan |first=Nathan |date=16 April 2018 |work=[[WalesOnline]] |access-date=13 September 2018}}</ref> A further 5,000 extras appeared in scenes at [[Gorleston-on-Sea]] Beach in [[Norfolk]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/danny-boyle-film-needs-extras-14659073 |title=Danny Boyle and Richard Curtis are looking for extras in Cambridgeshire |first=Alistair |last=Ryder |date=15 May 2018 |website=CambridgeshireLive |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Wembley Stadium was also used to film a concert scene.<ref name=\":0\" /> Filming also took place in [[Liverpool]], making use of [[Penny Lane, Liverpool|Penny Lane]], [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport]], [[Lime Street Station]] and the [[Queensway Tunnel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/if-you-make-film-beatles-16463828 |title=You can't make a film about The Beatles without going to Liverpool |last1=Hughes |first1=Lorna |date=24 June 2019 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, it was announced that the title of the film was ''Yesterday''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trailer-track.com/2019/02/11/in-the-pipeline-first-trailer-for-danny-boyle-writer-richard-curtiss-yesterday-ready-arriving-very-soon/ |title=In The Pipeline: First Trailer For Danny Boyle & Writer Richard Curtis's Yesterday Ready & Arriving Very Soon |date=11 February 2019 |website=Trailer Track |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> It is estimated to have cost around $10 million to get the rights for the Beatles' songs to be featured in the film, with the rights to their music being held by [[Apple Records]] and [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/danny-boyle-feared-yesterday-movie-might-upset-the-beatles/ |title=Danny Boyle Feared 'Yesterday' Movie Might Upset the Beatles |first=Martin |last=Kielty |date=24 May 2019 |website=Ultimate Classic Rock |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> Scenes with de Armas, who played another love interest for Jack, were cut as test audiences felt it made Jack less sympathetic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2475654/yesterday-cut-an-entire-character-from-the-film-that-would-have-changed-the-plot |title=Yesterday Cut An Entire Character From The Film That Would Have Changed The Plot |first=Mike|last=Reyes|date=26 June 2019 |website=CinemaBlend |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Yesterday'' was initially set for a September 2019 release, but was moved up to 28 June 2019, largely as a result of a copyright suit filed by [[Paul McCartney]]. The rights to some of the earlier Beatles songs used in the film would revert back to McCartney in the autumn of 2019, and [[Sony Music]] wanted to get ahead of it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/danny-boyle-richard-curtis-comedy-eyes-sept-2019-release-two-months-before-james-bond-1202365674/ |title=Danny Boyle-Richard Curtis Musical Comedy Tunes Up For Summer 2019 Release \u2013 Update |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=19 September 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe first official trailer of the film was released on 12 February 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=thr |author=Hollywood Reporter |date=13 February 2019 |number=1095470470655205376?s=19 |title='Yesterday' explores what would happen when only one man remembers The Beatles. Watch the trailer: https://t.yco/kDmQW36pwW}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] on 4 May 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/tribeca-slots-danny-boyles-yesterday-as-closing-night-film-gala-screenings-for-trey-anastasio-doc-apocalypse-now-say-anything-1202575642/ |title=Tribeca Slots Danny Boyle's 'Yesterday' As Closing-Night Film, Galas For Trey Anastasio Doc, 'Apocalypse Now,' 'Say Anything \u2026' |first=Dade |last=Hayes |date=14 March 2019 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> A local screening of the film took place at the [[Gorleston-on-Sea|Gorleston Palace]] cinema on 21 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/what-s-on/ed-sheeran-attends-norfolk-yesterday-premiere-with-danny-boyle-and-richard-curtis-1-6120165 |title=Ed Sheeran attends Gorleston premiere of Beatles-inspired film Yesterday |last=Steward |first=Michael |date=21 June 2019 |newspaper=[[East Anglian Daily Times]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Yesterday'' grossed $73.3{{nbsp}}million in the United States and Canada, and $80.4 {{nbsp}}million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $153.7{{nbsp}}million, against a production budget of $26{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $10\u201315 million from 2,603 theatres in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/toy-story-4-annabelle-comes-home-yesterday-box-office-preview-1202637662/ |title='Toy Story 4' Climbs To $135M+ Through 4-Days & Will Dominate Next Weekend Before 'Spider-Man' Swings In \u2013 Preview |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=25 June 2019 |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref> The film made $6.1 million on its first day, including $1.25 million from Thursday night previews. The opening day audiences were mostly aged over 25 (75%), female (56%), and Caucasian (65%). It ended up slightly exceeding projections and debuting to $17 million, finishing third behind ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' and ''[[Annabelle Comes Home]]''.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/toy-story-4-yesterday-annabelle-comes-home-weekend-box-office-1202639398/ |title='Toy Story 4' Holds Down No. 1 With $58M Before 'Spider-Man' Mania, 'Annabelle 3' Jump Scares To 31M+, 'Yesterday' $17M+ \u2013 Sunday Final |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=30 June 2019 |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref> In its second weekend the film made $10.7 million, again finishing in third (behind ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]'' and ''Toy Story 4''),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/spider-man-far-from-home-box-office-opening-record-july-4th-sony-marvel-1202642641/ |title='Spider-Man: Far From Home' Hooks $185M 6-Day Opening Records For Sony & Independence Day Holiday Stretch |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> then grossed $6.8 million in its third weekend, falling to fifth.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/spider-man-far-from-home-crawl-stuber-weekend-box-office-1202645451/ |title=Counterprogramming 'Crawl' & 'Stuber' Collateral Damage In Superhero Summer As 'Spider-Man' Climbs To $45M+ \u2013 Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=14 July 2019 |access-date=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn other territories, the film opened to {{US$|7.8 million|long=no}}, including $2.8 million in the United Kingdom (where it finished second behind ''Toy Story 4'') and $2.5 million in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=00&id=untitleddannyboyle.htm |title=Yesterday (2019) - International Box Office Results |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/toy-story-4-comfortably-holds-off-yesterday-at-uk-box-office/5140830.article |title='Toy Story 4' comfortably holds off 'Yesterday' at UK box office |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |date=1 July 2019 |website=[[Screen Daily]] |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 63% based on 338 reviews, with an average rating of 6.32/10. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Yesterday'' may fall short of fab, but the end result is still a sweetly charming fantasy with an intriguing\u2014albeit somewhat under-explored\u2014premise.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/yesterday_2019|title=Yesterday (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 56 out of 100, based on 44 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/yesterday|title=Yesterday (2019) Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an 87% overall positive score and a 63% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/toy-story-4-yesterday-annabelle-comes-home-weekend-box-office-1202639398/ |title='Toy Story 4' Holds Down No. 1 With $58M Before 'Spider-Man' Mania, 'Annabelle 3' Jump Scares To 31M+, 'Yesterday' $17M+ \u2013 Sunday Final |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=30 June 2019 |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film four out of five stars, writing \"although this film can be a bit hokey and uncertain on narrative development, the puppyish zest and fun summoned up by Curtis and Boyle carry it along.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/05/yesterday-review-the-beatles-richard-curtis-danny-boyle-himesh-patel |title=Yesterday review \u2013 Richard Curtis' magical mystery tour of a world without the Beatles |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |date=5 May 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> [[Robbie Collin]] also responded positively in his review for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', saying the film \"rallies in style for a beautifully judged and surprisingly moving finale, which owes a lot to Patel and James's chemistry.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/yesterday-review-danny-boyle-richard-curtis-beatles-make-surprisingly/ |title=Yesterday review: Danny Boyle and Richard Curtis make a dream duo |first=Robbie |last=Collin |date=5 May 2019 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-access=subscription |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', meanwhile, was less enthusiastic, claiming the film had little soul and calling it a \"rom-com wallpapered with the Beatles' greatness.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/yesterday-review-the-beatles-danny-boyle-1203205141/ |title='Yesterday' Review: A Fairy Tale in Which the Beatles Get Rebooted |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman |date=4 May 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> Laura Snapes of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called ''Yesterday'' \"the latest jukebox movie to put its women on mute.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jun/27/yesterday-music-films-women-danny-boyle|title=Yesterday: the latest jukebox movie to put its women on mute|first=Laura |last=Snapes |date=27 June 2019 |magazine=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcCartney and his wife Nancy Shevell snuck into a theater in [[The_Hamptons|The Hamptons]] to see it. They giggled at references to Paul, and loved the film.<ref> url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/paul-mccartney-secretly-snuck-cinema-watch-yesterday-loved-it-2574597 |title=Paul McCartney secretly snuck into a cinema to watch \u2018Yesterday\u2019 and \u201cloved it\u201d</ref>\n\n===Similarities===\n\nThe film drew comparisons to several other works dealing with a similar premise or theme.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/beatles-graphic-novel-yesterday-free-online-danny-boyle-1203253302/ |title=Graphic Novel 'Yesterday' From 2011 Similar to Danny Boyle Film Is Posted Online for Free |last=Keslassy |first=Elsa |date=2019-06-26 |magazine=Variety |access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/06/yesterday-danny-boyle-beatles-movie-similarities-novels-1202153249/ |title='Yesterday': Danny Boyle's Beatles-Centric Movie Shares Similarities With Two Different Novels |last=Erbland |first=Kate |date=2019-06-26 |website=IndieWire |access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> Similarities can be found in the 2011 French [[graphic novel]] ''Yesterday'' by David Blot and J\u00e9r\u00e9mie Royer,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/06/yesterday-graphic-novel-released-online-for-free.html |title=Graphic Novel with Same Name & Premise as Danny Boyle's Yesterday Released Online for Free |first=Savannah |last=Sicurella |date=26 June 2019 |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/vous-le-partagerez-aujourd-hui/vous-en-parlerez-aujourd-hui-yesterday-un-plagiat-d-aujourd-hui_3496333.html |title=Vous en parlerez aujourd'hui. \"Yesterday\", un plagiat d'aujourd'hui? |first=Jean-Mathieu |last=Pernin |date=2019-07-03 |website=[[France Info (TV channel)|Franceinfo:]] |language=fr |access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.franceculture.fr/emissions/le-billet-culturel/le-billet-culturel-du-vendredi-28-juin-2019 |title='Yesterday' de Danny Boyle, calqu\u00e9 sur une BD fran\u00e7aise? |date=28 June 2019 |website=[[France Culture]] |language=fr |accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref> the 2011 Japanese [[manga]] {{nihongo|''I'm a Beatle''|\u50d5\u306f\u30d3\u30fc\u30c8\u30eb\u30ba|Boku wa B\u012btoruzu}} by Tetsuo Fujii and [[Kaiji Kawaguchi]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://myanimelist.net/manga/23231/Boku_wa_Beatles |title=Boku wa Beatles |date=2012 |website=MyAnimeList.net |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mangarock.com/manga/mrs-serie-35018 |title=Boku wa Beatles |website=Manga Rock - Online Manga Reader |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> the 1990s British sitcom ''[[Goodnight Sweetheart (TV series)|Goodnight Sweetheart]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/apr/28/beatles-inspired-danny-boyle-film-yesterday |title=A world where the Beatles never existed inspires new Danny Boyle film |last1=Thorpe |first1=Vanessa |date=28 April 2019 |work=[[The Observer]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref> the 2006 French film ''[[Jean-Philippe (film)|Jean-Philippe]]'', and the 2013 novel ''Enormity'' by Nick Milligan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-02-18/yesterday-movie-plot-similar-to-australian-authors-story/10822006 |title=Australian author 'shattered' that his 2013 novel has resemblance to new film Yesterday |last=Hinchliffe |first=Jessica |date=18 February 2019 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212025934/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-02-18/yesterday-movie-plot-similar-to-australian-authors-story/10822006 |archive-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n==Trivia==\n*This film uses [[DuckDuckGo]].\n==See also==\n* ''[[Blinded by the Light (2019 film)|Blinded by the Light]]'', a 2019 British comedy-drama about an aspiring writer inspired by the songs of [[Bruce Springsteen]].\n* [[Isekai]], a Japanese fantasy subgenre where a normal person gets transported to another world.\n* [[Mandela effect]]\n* [[Parallel universes in fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|8079248}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|yesterday_2019|Yesterday}}\n\n{{Danny Boyle}}\n{{Richard Curtis}}\n{{The Beatles filmography and videography}}\n{{John Lennon}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:Alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American rock music films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:British alternative history films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British fantasy comedy films]]\n[[Category:British musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:British rock music films]]\n[[Category:British romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Chinese fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:Chinese musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:Chinese rock music films]]\n[[Category:Chinese romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John Lennon]]\n[[Category:Fantasy comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films about guitars and guitarists]]\n[[Category:Films about interracial romance]]\n[[Category:Films about singers]]\n[[Category:Films associated with the Beatles]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Danny Boyle]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Richard Curtis]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Eric Fellner]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Tim Bevan]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Daniel Pemberton]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2019]]\n[[Category:Films set in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Films set in Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Films set in Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Japanese alternate history films]]\n[[Category:Japanese comedy films]]\n[[Category:Japanese fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese musical films]]\n[[Category:Japanese rock music films]]\n[[Category:Japanese romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Jukebox musical films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Working Title Films films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Danny Boyle}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| image          = Yesterday (2019 poster).png\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Danny Boyle]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tim Bevan]]\n* [[Eric Fellner]]\n* Bernie Bellew\n* Matthew James Wilkinson\n* [[Richard Curtis]]\n* Danny Boyle\n}}\n| screenplay     = Richard Curtis\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Jack Barth\n* Richard Curtis\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Himesh Patel]]\n* [[Lily James]]\n* [[Ed Sheeran]]\n* [[Kate McKinnon]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Daniel Pemberton]]\n| cinematography = Christopher Ross\n| editing        = [[Jon Harris (director)|Jon Harris]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Perfect World Pictures]]\n* [[Working Title Films]]\n* Decibel Films\n* [[Dentsu Inc.]]<ref name=\"BFI\">{{cite web |title=Yesterday (2019) |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5ce28fc0a979f |website=BFI |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2019|5|4|[[Tribeca Film Festival|Tribeca]]|2019|06|28|United Kingdom & United States}}\n| country        = {{unbulleted list|United Kingdom|United States|China|Japan<ref name=\"BFI\"/>}}\n| runtime        = 116 minutes\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $26 million<ref name=\"BOM\" />\n| gross          = {{US$|153.7 million|long=no}}<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=untitleddannyboyle.htm |title=Yesterday (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Yesterday''''' is a 2019 [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Danny Boyle]] and screenplay by [[Richard Curtis]], based on a story by Jack Barth and Curtis.<ref name=\"ItzkoffNYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/movies/yesterday-movie-beatles-songs.html |title=The Long and Winding Road to 'Yesterday,' a Film Full of Beatles Music |last1=Itzkoff |first1=Dave |date=June 28, 2019 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.screendaily.com/features/the-story-behind-beatles-film-yesterday-richard-curtis-danny-boyle-working-title-and-a-rising-uk-producer/5138875.article |title=The story behind Beatles film 'Yesterday': Richard Curtis, Danny Boyle, Working Title and a rising UK producer |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |date=3 May 2019 |website=[[Screen Daily]] |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> The film, named after [[Yesterday (Beatles song)|the song of the same name]] written by [[John Lennon]] and [[Paul McCartney]], stars [[Himesh Patel]] as a struggling musician Jack Malik, who, after an accident, finds himself the only person who remembers [[The Beatles]] and becomes famous after taking credit for their songs. The film also stars [[Lily James]] as the protagonist's childhood friend and love interest, [[Kate McKinnon]] as his obnoxious manager, and [[Ed Sheeran]] as a fictionalised version of himself.\n\nThe project was announced in March 2018. Filming began the following month around England, particularly [[Norfolk]] and Halesworth in Suffolk. Photography also took place at [[Wembley Stadium]], [[Millennium Stadium|Principality Stadium]] and in [[Los Angeles]]. The filmmakers paid $10 million for the rights to use [[The Beatles discography|the Beatles' music]]; although none of the members were involved, Boyle received approval for the project from them and their families.\n\n''Yesterday'' had its world premiere at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] on 4 May 2019,<ref name=\"2019-03-14 Variety\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/tribeca-danny-boyle-yesterday-closing-night-film-1203162974/ |title=Danny Boyle's Beatles Movie 'Yesterday' Selected as Tribeca Closing Night Film |last1=McNary |first1=Dave |date=14 March 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |issn=0042-2738 |oclc=810134503 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331031320/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/tribeca-danny-boyle-yesterday-closing-night-film-1203162974/ |archive-date=31 March 2019}}</ref> and was released in the United Kingdom and the United States on 28 June 2019, by [[Universal Pictures]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/danny-boyles-lily-james-kate-mckinnon-comedy-lands-fall-2019-release-1103183 |title=Danny Boyle's Lily James-Kate McKinnon Comedy Lands Fall 2019 Release |first=Pamela |last=McClintock |date=16 April 2018 |newspaper=[[Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> The film grossed $153 million worldwide against a production budget of $26 million. It received mixed reviews from critics, with praise for the premise, performances, and [[musical film|musical]] sequences, but criticism of the familiarity and not taking the concept further.\n\n==Plot==\nJack Malik is a struggling singer-songwriter from [[Lowestoft]]. His manager and childhood friend Ellie Appleton encourages him not to give up on his dreams. During a global blackout, Jack is hit by a bus. After recovering, he sings the [[the Beatles|Beatles]] song \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\" for his friends, and discovers they have never heard of the Beatles. After realising no one in the world remembers them, Jack begins performing Beatles songs, passing them off as his own.\n\nEllie has Jack record a demo with a local music producer, Gavin. While recording day and night in Gavin's recording room, Malik published and gave out his album to every customer he sees back at Lowestoft. Following a performance on local television, Jack is invited by pop star [[Ed Sheeran]] to play as his opening act in Moscow. Ellie declines to join him, saying she must work at her day job as a schoolteacher, so Jack's [[Road crew|roadie]] friend Rocky travels with him instead. After the gig, Sheeran challenges Jack to a songwriting duel; he loses to Jack's \"[[The Long and Winding Road]]\". In Los Angeles, Sheeran's ruthless manager Debra Hammer signs him to her label and engineers his rise to global fame.\n\nAt Jack's going-away party, Ellie confesses that she has always been in love with him. Jack goes back to Los Angeles and starts recording the album at [[EastWest Studios]], but cannot remember the lyrics for the song he was trying to \"write,\" \"[[Eleanor Rigby]].\" Hoping to trigger memories, Jack goes to the Beatles' hometown of [[Liverpool]], visiting landmarks such as [[Strawberry Field]], [[Penny Lane, Liverpool|Penny Lane]], and the grave of [[Eleanor Rigby#Real people named Eleanor Rigby|Eleanor Rigby]]. Ellie joins him in Liverpool, and they spend a drunken evening and kiss, but Ellie tells him she is not interested in a one-night stand. The next morning, Jack and Rocky pursue Ellie to the train station, where she congratulates Jack but tells him she cannot be a part of his celebrity life. Jack returns to Los Angeles, heartbroken; Ellie begins dating Gavin.\n\nThe record label prepares to launch Jack's debut album. The producers reject his suggested titles, taken from Beatles records, and name the album ''One Man Only'', pushing his talent. Jack persuades them to launch the album with a [[The Beatles' rooftop concert|rooftop concert]] in [[Gorleston-on-Sea]]. Backstage, two fans approach him and tell him they know he plagiarised the songs, but thank him, having feared the Beatles' music was gone forever. They give him the address of [[John Lennon]], who has survived into old age, out of the public spotlight. John, who has lived a happy life with his wife, advises Jack to pursue the one he loves and always tell the truth.\n\nSheeran arranges for Jack to perform at [[Wembley Stadium]]. Jack confesses to the crowd that he plagiarised the music and that he loves Ellie, and has Rocky upload the songs free to the internet, sabotaging the record release, much to Debra\u2019s anger, who is enraged over Jack\u2019s confession. \n\nEventually, Jack and Ellie marry and have a family together, and Jack becomes a music teacher. During the story Jack also discovers other things have disappeared, such as [[Coca-Cola]], [[cigarettes]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], and [[Harry Potter]].\n\n==Cast==\n<!--- Cast and order per tombstone closing credits, roles per closing credits scroll --->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Himesh Patel]] as Jack Malik\n* [[Lily James]] as Ellie Appleton\n* [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] as Rocky\n* [[Ed Sheeran]] as himself\n* [[Kate McKinnon]] as Debra Hammer\n* [[Sanjeev Bhaskar]] as Jed Malik\n* [[Meera Syal]] as Shelia Malik\n* Harry Michell as Nick\n* [[Sophia Di Martino]] as Carol\n* [[Sarah Lancashire]] as Liz (Liverpool stranger)\n* [[Alexander Arnold (actor)|Alexander Arnold]] as Gavin\n* [[Lamorne Morris]] as Head of Marketing\n}}\n\nIn addition, [[James Corden]] (hosting his show) and [[Michael Kiwanuka]] (waiting for Rocky to bring guitar) appear as themselves, [[Justin Edwards (actor)|Justin Edwards]] plays Leo (the Russian stranger who remembers the Beatles), and [[Robert Carlyle]] makes an uncredited appearance as [[John Lennon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/yesterday-movie-john-lennon-actor-robert-carlyle/ |title=Who Plays [SPOILER] In Yesterday? |first=John |last=Orquiola |date=28 June 2019 |work=[[Screen Rant]] |accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nThe film began as an original screenplay called ''Cover Version'', by writer Jack Barth and actor-writer-director [[Mackenzie Crook]], with Crook intending to direct the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-nowhere-man-behind-the-yesterday-script-11561392902? |title='Yesterday': The Real Story Behind The Beatles-Inspired Movie |last1=Watson |first1=R. T. |date=6 June 2019 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/inside-making-yesterday-beatles-ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-richard-curtis-846248/ |title=How 'Yesterday' Breathes New Life Into the Beatles' Music |last1=Browne |first1=David |date=25 June 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ItzkoffNYT\" /> A few years later, after Crook had dropped out due to other commitments, the story was pitched to writer-director [[Richard Curtis]], who loved the idea but wanted to write his own script for it. Whereas in ''Cover Version'', the lead character achieves only moderate success with the Beatles songs, Curtis's lead character becomes the world's most celebrated singer-songwriter. Curtis also shifted focus onto the love story between the male and female leads.\n\nIn March 2018, it was announced that director [[Danny Boyle]] and writer Richard Curtis were working together on a [[Musical comedy film|musical comedy]] that would be set in the 1960s or 1970s and centre on \"a struggling musician who thinks he's the only person who can remember [[The Beatles]]\" with [[Himesh Patel]] cast in the lead role.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/danny-boyle-richard-curtis-team-universal-comedy-1089881 |title=Danny Boyle, Richard Curtis Team for Universal Comedy |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=1 March 2018 |newspaper=[[Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> [[Ed Sheeran]]'s supporting role was originally intended for [[Chris Martin]], who turned it down.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/yesterday-ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-beatles-1202153594/ |title='Yesterday': Ed Sheeran's Smart Casting Advice Saved Danny Boyle's Beatles Rom-Com |last1=Thompson |first1=Anne |date=2 July 2019 |website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref> For the lead role, Patel was selected from the many actors who auditioned, with Boyle convinced Patel was the right choice after listening to him perform \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\" and \"[[Back in the U.S.S.R.]]\" during auditions.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/features/yesterday-movie-beatles-danny-boyle-interview-1203249029/ |title=Danny Boyle on 'Yesterday,' Leaving 'Bond 25' and Why the Beatles Still Rock |last1=Rubin |first1=Rebecca |date=25 June 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=2 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Boyle felt that Patel's voice had soul; Sheeran agreed.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> In addition to acting, the Beatles cover songs in the film are sung by Patel, who also plays the guitar and piano.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.classicfm.com/discover-music/does-himesh-patel-sing-play-guitar-yesterday-movie/ |title=Does Himesh Patel sing and play guitar in Yesterday the movie? |date=1 July 2019 |website=[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] |accessdate=2 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\nLater in March 2018, [[Lily James]] and [[Kate McKinnon]] joined the cast.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lily-james-talks-star-danny-boyle-comedy-1093179 |title=Lily James in Talks to Star in Danny Boyle Comedy (Exclusive) |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=8 March 2018 |newspaper=Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kate-mckinnon-talks-join-lily-james-danny-boyle-comedy-1098509 |title=Kate McKinnon in Talks to Join Lily James in Danny Boyle Comedy |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=30 March 2018 |newspaper=Hollywood Reporter |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Boyle informed the surviving members and widows of the band about the film and received a reply he described as \"lovely\" from Beatles drummer [[Ringo Starr]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.picturehouses.com/blog/the-big-interview-danny-boyle |title=The Big Interview: Danny Boyle |first=James |last=Mottram |date=26 April 2019 |website=[[Picturehouse Cinemas|Picturehouse]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> In April 2018, it was revealed that Ed Sheeran had joined the cast and would potentially also write new music for the film, which would also include Beatles songs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/ed-sheeran-in-talks-for-danny-boyle-working-title-beatles-musical-1202364467/ |title=Ed Sheeran In Talks For Danny Boyle-Richard Curtis Music-Themed Comedy Movie |first=Andreas |last=Wiseman |date=15 April 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/ed-sheeran-danny-boyle-musical-comedy-movie-beatles/ |title=Ed Sheeran in Talks to Join Danny Boyle's Beatles-Themed Musical Comedy |first=Adam |last=Chitwood |authorlink=Adam Chitwood |work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] | date=15 April 2018 |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> Later that month, [[Ana de Armas]] and [[Lamorne Morris]] had also joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/ana-de-armas-danny-boyle-untitled-romantic-comedy-universal-1202375910/ |title=Ana de Armas Makes A Date With Danny Boyle Untitled Romantic Comedy |first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |date=24 April 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/new-girl-lamorne-morris-danny-boyle-untitled-comedy-casting-1202378296/ |title='New Girl's Lamorne Morris Joins Universal's Danny Boyle-Richard Curtis Comedy |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=27 April 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> In May 2018, [[Sophia Di Martino]], [[Joel Fry (actor)|Joel Fry]] and Harry Michell joined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/danny-boyle-untitled-romantic-comedy-james-bond-casting-1202385464/ |title=Danny Boyle & Richard Curtis Untitled Romantic Comedy Adds Three |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=8 May 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nFilming began on 21 April 2018,<ref>{{cite tweet |first=Emma |last=Freud |user=emmafreud |number=987757367407333376 |title=We began shooting our new movie today |date=21 April 2018 |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> with production in the United Kingdom starting on 26 April 2018, with scenes filmed all around Suffolk in [[Cantley, Norfolk|Cantley]], [[Halesworth]], [[Dunwich]], [[Shingle Street]], [[Latitude Festival]] and [[Clacton-on-Sea]], [[Essex]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/16187446.Danny_Boyle_s_new_Beatles_musical_is_being_filmed_in_north_Essex/ |title=Danny Boyle's new Beatles musical was being filmed in north Essex |first=Chris |last=Wilkin |date=26 April 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Gazette (Colchester)|Daily Gazette]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> A casting call was issued for extras in overnight scenes shot immediately after Sheeran's four consecutive concerts at the [[Millennium Stadium|Principality Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]] in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/ed-sheeran-rumoured-danny-boyles-14535623 |title=Ed Sheeran is rumoured to be in Danny Boyle's new film |last=Bevan |first=Nathan |date=16 April 2018 |work=[[WalesOnline]] |access-date=13 September 2018}}</ref> A further 5,000 extras appeared in scenes at [[Gorleston-on-Sea]] Beach in [[Norfolk]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/danny-boyle-film-needs-extras-14659073 |title=Danny Boyle and Richard Curtis are looking for extras in Cambridgeshire |first=Alistair |last=Ryder |date=15 May 2018 |website=CambridgeshireLive |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Wembley Stadium was also used to film a concert scene.<ref name=\":0\" /> Filming also took place in [[Liverpool]], making use of [[Penny Lane, Liverpool|Penny Lane]], [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport]], [[Lime Street Station]] and the [[Queensway Tunnel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/if-you-make-film-beatles-16463828 |title=You can't make a film about The Beatles without going to Liverpool |last1=Hughes |first1=Lorna |date=24 June 2019 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |accessdate=13 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, it was announced that the title of the film was ''Yesterday''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trailer-track.com/2019/02/11/in-the-pipeline-first-trailer-for-danny-boyle-writer-richard-curtiss-yesterday-ready-arriving-very-soon/ |title=In The Pipeline: First Trailer For Danny Boyle & Writer Richard Curtis's Yesterday Ready & Arriving Very Soon |date=11 February 2019 |website=Trailer Track |accessdate=11 February 2019}}</ref> It is estimated to have cost around $10 million to get the rights for the Beatles' songs to be featured in the film, with the rights to their music being held by [[Apple Records]] and [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/danny-boyle-feared-yesterday-movie-might-upset-the-beatles/ |title=Danny Boyle Feared 'Yesterday' Movie Might Upset the Beatles |first=Martin |last=Kielty |date=24 May 2019 |website=Ultimate Classic Rock |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> Scenes with de Armas, who played another love interest for Jack, were cut as test audiences felt it made Jack less sympathetic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2475654/yesterday-cut-an-entire-character-from-the-film-that-would-have-changed-the-plot |title=Yesterday Cut An Entire Character From The Film That Would Have Changed The Plot |first=Mike|last=Reyes|date=26 June 2019 |website=CinemaBlend |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Yesterday'' was initially set for a September 2019 release, but was moved up to 28 June 2019, largely as a result of a copyright suit filed by [[Paul McCartney]]. The rights to some of the earlier Beatles songs used in the film would revert back to McCartney in the autumn of 2019, and [[Sony Music]] wanted to get ahead of it.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/danny-boyle-richard-curtis-comedy-eyes-sept-2019-release-two-months-before-james-bond-1202365674/ |title=Danny Boyle-Richard Curtis Musical Comedy Tunes Up For Summer 2019 Release \u2013 Update |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=19 September 2018 |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe first official trailer of the film was released on 12 February 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=thr |author=Hollywood Reporter |date=13 February 2019 |number=1095470470655205376?s=19 |title='Yesterday' explores what would happen when only one man remembers The Beatles. Watch the trailer: https://t.yco/kDmQW36pwW}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] on 4 May 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/tribeca-slots-danny-boyles-yesterday-as-closing-night-film-gala-screenings-for-trey-anastasio-doc-apocalypse-now-say-anything-1202575642/ |title=Tribeca Slots Danny Boyle's 'Yesterday' As Closing-Night Film, Galas For Trey Anastasio Doc, 'Apocalypse Now,' 'Say Anything \u2026' |first=Dade |last=Hayes |date=14 March 2019 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> A local screening of the film took place at the [[Gorleston-on-Sea|Gorleston Palace]] cinema on 21 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/what-s-on/ed-sheeran-attends-norfolk-yesterday-premiere-with-danny-boyle-and-richard-curtis-1-6120165 |title=Ed Sheeran attends Gorleston premiere of Beatles-inspired film Yesterday |last=Steward |first=Michael |date=21 June 2019 |newspaper=[[East Anglian Daily Times]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Yesterday'' grossed $73.3{{nbsp}}million in the United States and Canada, and $80.4 {{nbsp}}million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $153.7{{nbsp}}million, against a production budget of $26{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was projected to gross $10\u201315 million from 2,603 theatres in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/toy-story-4-annabelle-comes-home-yesterday-box-office-preview-1202637662/ |title='Toy Story 4' Climbs To $135M+ Through 4-Days & Will Dominate Next Weekend Before 'Spider-Man' Swings In \u2013 Preview |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=25 June 2019 |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref> The film made $6.1 million on its first day, including $1.25 million from Thursday night previews. The opening day audiences were mostly aged over 25 (75%), female (56%), and Caucasian (65%). It ended up slightly exceeding projections and debuting to $17 million, finishing third behind ''[[Toy Story 4]]'' and ''[[Annabelle Comes Home]]''.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/toy-story-4-yesterday-annabelle-comes-home-weekend-box-office-1202639398/ |title='Toy Story 4' Holds Down No. 1 With $58M Before 'Spider-Man' Mania, 'Annabelle 3' Jump Scares To 31M+, 'Yesterday' $17M+ \u2013 Sunday Final |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=30 June 2019 |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref> In its second weekend the film made $10.7 million, again finishing in third (behind ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]'' and ''Toy Story 4''),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/spider-man-far-from-home-box-office-opening-record-july-4th-sony-marvel-1202642641/ |title='Spider-Man: Far From Home' Hooks $185M 6-Day Opening Records For Sony & Independence Day Holiday Stretch |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> then grossed $6.8 million in its third weekend, falling to fifth.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/spider-man-far-from-home-crawl-stuber-weekend-box-office-1202645451/ |title=Counterprogramming 'Crawl' & 'Stuber' Collateral Damage In Superhero Summer As 'Spider-Man' Climbs To $45M+ \u2013 Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=14 July 2019 |access-date=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn other territories, the film opened to {{US$|7.8 million|long=no}}, including $2.8 million in the United Kingdom (where it finished second behind ''Toy Story 4'') and $2.5 million in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=00&id=untitleddannyboyle.htm |title=Yesterday (2019) - International Box Office Results |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/toy-story-4-comfortably-holds-off-yesterday-at-uk-box-office/5140830.article |title='Toy Story 4' comfortably holds off 'Yesterday' at UK box office |last1=Grater |first1=Tom |date=1 July 2019 |website=[[Screen Daily]] |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 63% based on 338 reviews, with an average rating of 6.32/10. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Yesterday'' may fall short of fab, but the end result is still a sweetly charming fantasy with an intriguing\u2014albeit somewhat under-explored\u2014premise.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/yesterday_2019|title=Yesterday (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 56 out of 100, based on 44 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/yesterday|title=Yesterday (2019) Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an 87% overall positive score and a 63% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/toy-story-4-yesterday-annabelle-comes-home-weekend-box-office-1202639398/ |title='Toy Story 4' Holds Down No. 1 With $58M Before 'Spider-Man' Mania, 'Annabelle 3' Jump Scares To 31M+, 'Yesterday' $17M+ \u2013 Sunday Final |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=30 June 2019 |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film four out of five stars, writing \"although this film can be a bit hokey and uncertain on narrative development, the puppyish zest and fun summoned up by Curtis and Boyle carry it along.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/may/05/yesterday-review-the-beatles-richard-curtis-danny-boyle-himesh-patel |title=Yesterday review \u2013 Richard Curtis' magical mystery tour of a world without the Beatles |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |date=5 May 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> [[Robbie Collin]] also responded positively in his review for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', saying the film \"rallies in style for a beautifully judged and surprisingly moving finale, which owes a lot to Patel and James's chemistry.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/yesterday-review-danny-boyle-richard-curtis-beatles-make-surprisingly/ |title=Yesterday review: Danny Boyle and Richard Curtis make a dream duo |first=Robbie |last=Collin |date=5 May 2019 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-access=subscription |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', meanwhile, was less enthusiastic, claiming the film had little soul and calling it a \"rom-com wallpapered with the Beatles' greatness.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/yesterday-review-the-beatles-danny-boyle-1203205141/ |title='Yesterday' Review: A Fairy Tale in Which the Beatles Get Rebooted |first=Owen |last=Gleiberman |date=4 May 2019 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> Laura Snapes of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called ''Yesterday'' \"the latest jukebox movie to put its women on mute.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jun/27/yesterday-music-films-women-danny-boyle|title=Yesterday: the latest jukebox movie to put its women on mute|first=Laura |last=Snapes |date=27 June 2019 |magazine=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcCartney and his wife Nancy Shevell snuck into a theater in [[The_Hamptons|The Hamptons]] to see it. They giggled at references to Paul, and loved the film.<ref> url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/paul-mccartney-secretly-snuck-cinema-watch-yesterday-loved-it-2574597 |title=Paul McCartney secretly snuck into a cinema to watch \u2018Yesterday\u2019 and \u201cloved it\u201d</ref>\n\n===Similarities===\n\nThe film drew comparisons to several other works dealing with a similar premise or theme.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/beatles-graphic-novel-yesterday-free-online-danny-boyle-1203253302/ |title=Graphic Novel 'Yesterday' From 2011 Similar to Danny Boyle Film Is Posted Online for Free |last=Keslassy |first=Elsa |date=2019-06-26 |magazine=Variety |access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/06/yesterday-danny-boyle-beatles-movie-similarities-novels-1202153249/ |title='Yesterday': Danny Boyle's Beatles-Centric Movie Shares Similarities With Two Different Novels |last=Erbland |first=Kate |date=2019-06-26 |website=IndieWire |access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> Similarities can be found in the 2011 French [[graphic novel]] ''Yesterday'' by David Blot and J\u00e9r\u00e9mie Royer,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2019/06/yesterday-graphic-novel-released-online-for-free.html |title=Graphic Novel with Same Name & Premise as Danny Boyle's Yesterday Released Online for Free |first=Savannah |last=Sicurella |date=26 June 2019 |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/vous-le-partagerez-aujourd-hui/vous-en-parlerez-aujourd-hui-yesterday-un-plagiat-d-aujourd-hui_3496333.html |title=Vous en parlerez aujourd'hui. \"Yesterday\", un plagiat d'aujourd'hui? |first=Jean-Mathieu |last=Pernin |date=2019-07-03 |website=[[France Info (TV channel)|Franceinfo:]] |language=fr |access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.franceculture.fr/emissions/le-billet-culturel/le-billet-culturel-du-vendredi-28-juin-2019 |title='Yesterday' de Danny Boyle, calqu\u00e9 sur une BD fran\u00e7aise? |date=28 June 2019 |website=[[France Culture]] |language=fr |accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref> the 2011 Japanese [[manga]] {{nihongo|''I'm a Beatle''|\u50d5\u306f\u30d3\u30fc\u30c8\u30eb\u30ba|Boku wa B\u012btoruzu}} by Tetsuo Fujii and [[Kaiji Kawaguchi]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://myanimelist.net/manga/23231/Boku_wa_Beatles |title=Boku wa Beatles |date=2012 |website=MyAnimeList.net |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mangarock.com/manga/mrs-serie-35018 |title=Boku wa Beatles |website=Manga Rock - Online Manga Reader |access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref> the 1990s British sitcom ''[[Goodnight Sweetheart (TV series)|Goodnight Sweetheart]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/apr/28/beatles-inspired-danny-boyle-film-yesterday |title=A world where the Beatles never existed inspires new Danny Boyle film |last1=Thorpe |first1=Vanessa |date=28 April 2019 |work=[[The Observer]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |accessdate=4 July 2019}}</ref> the 2006 French film ''[[Jean-Philippe (film)|Jean-Philippe]]'', and the 2013 novel ''Enormity'' by Nick Milligan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-02-18/yesterday-movie-plot-similar-to-australian-authors-story/10822006 |title=Australian author 'shattered' that his 2013 novel has resemblance to new film Yesterday |last=Hinchliffe |first=Jessica |date=18 February 2019 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212025934/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-02-18/yesterday-movie-plot-similar-to-australian-authors-story/10822006 |archive-date=12 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Blinded by the Light (2019 film)|Blinded by the Light]]'', a 2019 British comedy-drama about an aspiring writer inspired by the songs of [[Bruce Springsteen]].\n* [[Isekai]], a Japanese fantasy subgenre where a normal person gets transported to another world.\n* [[Mandela effect]]\n* [[Parallel universes in fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|8079248}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|yesterday_2019|Yesterday}}\n\n{{Danny Boyle}}\n{{Richard Curtis}}\n{{The Beatles filmography and videography}}\n{{John Lennon}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:Alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American rock music films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:British alternative history films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n