ok |last=Ryan |first=Mary P. |authorlink=Mary P. Ryan |title=Cradle of the middle class : the family in Oneida County, New York, 1790-1865 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |publication-place=Cambridge, Eng. New York |year=1981 |isbn=9780521274036 |oclc=1029047763 |url=https://archive.org/details/cradleofmiddlecl00mary}}\n*{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Goldwin |authorlink=Goldwin Smith |chapter=The Oneida Community and American Socialism |title=Essays on questions of the day, political and social |publisher=Macmillan |publication-place=New York and London |year=1893 |isbn=9780665137341 |oclc=655456380 |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/essaysonquestion00smitrich#page/336/mode/2up |pages=337\u2013360}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Spears |first=Timothy B |title=Circles of Grace: Passion and Control in the Thought of John Humphrey Noyes |journal=New York History |volume=70 |issue=1 |date=January 1989 |oclc=5543224578 |issn=0146-437X |via=JSTOR |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23178171 |pages=79-103}}\n*{{cite web |last=Spurlock |first=John C. |title=Free Love: Marriage and Middle-Class Radicalism in America, 1825-1860 |publisher=New York University Press |publication-place=New York |year=1988 |isbn=9780814778838 |oclc=1035091152 |url=https://archive.org/details/freelovemarriage00spur}}{{Page needed|date=April 2020}}\n*{{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Robert |title=The man who would be perfect : John Humphrey Noyes and the Utopian impulse |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |publication-place=Philadelphia |year=1977 |isbn=9781512807592  |oclc=557939559 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctv4s7j9r |url-access=subscription |doi=10.9783/9781512807592}}<!--Do not remove URL or DOI; they are different sources.-->\n*{{cite journal |last=Warfield |first=Benjamin Breckinridge |title=John Humphrey Noyes and his 'Bible Communists' |journal=Bibliotheca Sacra |oclc=1046871046 |url=https://archive.org/details/johnhump00warf |volume=78 |number=309 |date=January 1921 |issn=0006-1921 |publisher=Bibliotheca Sacra Company |publication-place=Oberlin, OH |pages=37\u201372}}\n*{{cite journal |last=White |first=Janet R |title=Designed for Perfection: Intersections between Architecture and Social Program at the Oneida Community |journal=Utopian Studies |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=113-138 |year=1996 |oclc=5542761712 |issn=1045-991X |via=JSTOR |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/20719513}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.oneidacommunity.org/ Oneida Community Mansion House]&nbsp;\u2013 a museum of the Oneida Community\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130729144853/http://library.syr.edu/find/scrc/collections/diglib/oneida/ Oneida Community Digital Collection at Syracuse University]\n* [http://library.syr.edu/digital/guides/o/oneida_comm.htm Oneida Community Archives] at [[Syracuse University]]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/nationalmagazine23brayrich#page/n277/mode/1up ''1905 Magazine Article''] (with photos)\n\n{{Coord|43|3|37.28|N|75|36|18.63|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Communalism]]\n[[Category:Free love]]\n[[Category:Intentional communities in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Oneida, New York]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1848]]\n[[Category:Utopian communities]]\n", "name_user": "Peaceray", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSources:removed obsolete |ref=harv", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oneida_Community"}
{"title_page": "Darko Mavrak", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Darko Mavrak\n| fullname = Darko Mavrak\n| image = Mavrak, Darko.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1969|01|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Mostar]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| height =\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1989\u20131992 | clubs1 = [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]] | caps1 = 35 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 1992\u20131993 | clubs2 = [[FK Proleter Zrenjanin|Proleter Zrenjanin]] | caps2 = | goals2 =\n| years3 = 1993\u20131995 | clubs3 = [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] | caps3 = 50 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs4 = [[IFK Norrk\u00f6ping]] | caps4 = 26 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 1997 | clubs5 = [[Panachaiki 2005 F.C.|Panachaiki]] | caps5 = 8 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 1998 | clubs6 = [[Falkenbergs FF|Falkenberg]] | caps6 = 8 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 1998\u20132000 | clubs7 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] | caps7 = 17 | goals7 = 2\n| years8 = 2001 | clubs8 = [[Hapoel Tzafririm Holon F.C.|Hapoel Tzafririm Holon]] | caps8 = 12 | goals8 = 2\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =\n}}\n'''Darko Mavrak''' (born 19 January 1969) is a former [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] [[association football|footballer]].\n\nMavrak began his career with [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar]] in the [[Yugoslav First League]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Strukljeva |title=MAVRAK Darko |url=http://www.strukljeva.net/football/s_u_player.asp?id=3649 |accessdate=2009-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724084158/http://www.strukljeva.net/football/s_u_player.asp?id=3649 |archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> He played with [[FK Proleter Zrenjanin]] in the [[1992\u201393 First League of FR Yugoslavia]].<ref>[http://www.redstarbelgrade.info/forum/index.php?topic=3268.0 1992/93 season] at redstarbelgrade.info</ref> He moved to Swedish sides [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] and [[IFK Norrk\u00f6ping]] because of the [[Yugoslav Wars|War in Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite news| title=The Sweeper: They're not all Dennis Bergkamp; Unsung foreign legionnaires No 35|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/the-1087829.html | work=The Independent | location=London | date=1999-04-17 | accessdate=2010-05-01}}</ref> He had a brief spell with [[Panachaiki 2005 F.C.|Panachaiki F.C.]] in the [[Greek Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]] |author=Mastrogiannopoulos, Alexander |title=Foreign Players in Greece since 1959/60 |url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/foreign-players-in-grk6080.html |date=2005-02-02 |accessdate=2009-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210204039/http://www.rsssf.com/players/foreign-players-in-grk6080.html |archivedate=10 December 2008}}</ref> Mavrak finished his career with [[Walsall F.C.]] in [[England]]<ref>{{soccerbase|16380}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Birmingham Mail|Evening Mail]]|title=Walsall foreign legion|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-17570593.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102054408/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-17570593.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-02|date=1999-02-02}}</ref> and [[Hapoel Tzafririm Holon F.C.]] in [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|author=Bleicher, Yaniv|title=Israel Squads Premier League 2000/01|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/isra01squads.html|date=2001-05-31|accessdate=2009-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Darko Mavrak at playerhistory.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mavrak, Darko}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina footballers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece players]]\n[[Category:FK Vele\u017e Mostar players]]\n[[Category:FK Proleter Zrenjanin players]]\n[[Category:Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll players]]\n[[Category:IFK Norrk\u00f6ping players]]\n[[Category:Panachaiki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Falkenbergs FF players]]\n[[Category:Walsall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hapoel Tzafririm Holon F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Israel]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mostar]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{BosniaHerzegovina-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Darko Mavrak\n| fullname = Darko Mavrak\n| image = Mavrak, Darko.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1969|01|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Mostar]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| height =\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1989\u20131992 | clubs1 = [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]] | caps1 = 35 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 1992\u20131993 | clubs2 = [[FK Proleter Zrenjanin|Proleter Zrenjanin]] | caps2 = | goals2 =\n| years3 = 1993\u20131995 | clubs3 = [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] | caps3 = 50 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs4 = [[IFK Norrk\u00f6ping]] | caps4 = 26 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 1997 | clubs5 = [[Panachaiki 2005 F.C.|Panachaiki]] | caps5 = 8 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 1998 | clubs6 = [[Falkenbergs FF|Falkenberg]] | caps6 = 8 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 1998\u20132000 | clubs7 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] | caps7 = 17 | goals7 = 2\n| years8 = 2001 | clubs8 = [[Hapoel Tzafririm Holon F.C.|Hapoel Tzafririm Holon]] | caps8 = 12 | goals8 = 2\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 =\n}}\n'''Darko Mavrak''' (born 19 January 1969) is a former [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] [[association football|footballer]].\n\nMavrak began his career with [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar]] in the [[Yugoslav First League]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Strukljeva |title=MAVRAK Darko |url=http://www.strukljeva.net/football/s_u_player.asp?id=3649 |accessdate=2009-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724084158/http://www.strukljeva.net/football/s_u_player.asp?id=3649 |archivedate=24 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> He played with [[FK Proleter Zrenjanin]] in the [[1992\u201393 First League of FR Yugoslavia]].<ref>[http://www.redstarbelgrade.info/forum/index.php?topic=3268.0 1992/93 season] at redstarbelgrade.info</ref>  He moved to Swedish sides [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF Fotboll|Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] and [[IFK Norrk\u00f6ping]] because of the [[Yugoslav Wars|War in Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite news| title=The Sweeper: They're not all Dennis Bergkamp; Unsung foreign legionnaires No 35|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/the-1087829.html | work=The Independent | location=London | date=1999-04-17 | accessdate=2010-05-01}}</ref> He had a brief spell with [[Panachaiki 2005 F.C.|Panachaiki F.C.]] in the [[Greek Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]] |author=Mastrogiannopoulos, Alexander |title=Foreign Players in Greece since 1959/60 |url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/foreign-players-in-grk6080.html |date=2005-02-02 |accessdate=2009-10-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210204039/http://www.rsssf.com/players/foreign-players-in-grk6080.html |archivedate=10 December 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> Mavrak finished his career with [[Walsall F.C.]] in [[England]]<ref>{{soccerbase|16380}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Birmingham Mail|Evening Mail]]|title=Walsall foreign legion|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-17570593.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102054408/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-17570593.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-02|date=1999-02-02}}</ref> and [[Hapoel Tzafririm Holon F.C.]] in [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|author=Bleicher, Yaniv|title=Israel Squads Premier League 2000/01|url=http://www.rsssf.co