{"title_page": "Geoffrey de Gorham", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=November 2018}}\n\n'''Geoffrey de Gorham''' (Goreham, [[Gorron]]), sometimes called Geoffrey of Dunstable or of Le Mans (died at [[St Albans]], 26 February 1146), was a [[Normans|Norman]] scholar who became [[Abbot of St Albans Abbey]], 1119 to 1146.{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Life==\nHe was from the [[Maine (province)|province of Maine]], then annexed to the [[Dukedom of Normandy]]. He was invited by Richard d'Aubeney, Abbot of St Albans, to become master of the [[St Albans School (Hertfordshire)|Abbey school]]. On his arrival, he found that owing to his long delay another had been appointed, whereupon he opened a school at [[Dunstable]].{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nHe staged a [[miracle play]] on [[Catherine of Alexandria|St. Katherine]]. A chronicle relates how he had borrowed some [[cope]]s from [[St Albans Cathedral|St Albans Abbey]] for the performance, but had the misfortune to lose his books and the copes in a fire at his house in the night after the performance. To make up to God and the saint for the loss of the copes, he determined to become a monk of St Albans Abbey.<ref>Richard Axton, ''European Drama of the Early Middle Ages'' (1974), p. 161.</ref> \n\nHere he rose to be prior, and finally was elected abbot on the death of Richard, in 1119. He ruled for twenty-six years, and the abbey prospered. He succeeded in saving the Abbey when it was threatened with destruction during [[the Anarchy]] during the reign of King [[Stephen of England|Stephen]].{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nHe added to the building an infirmary with chapel attached, and spent large sums on a new shrine to which he translated the body of [[Saint Alban|St Alban]], 2 August 1129. {{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nGeoffrey endowed the nunnery at [[Sopwell Priory|Sopwell]], and founded another at [[Markyate]], in [[Hertfordshire]], for his friend and counsellor, [[Christina of Markyate]] the [[recluse]]. He also opened a [[leper hospital]] near St Albans.{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==References==\n\n;Attribution\n*{{Catholic|wstitle=Geoffrey of Dunstable}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geoffrey De Gorham}}\n[[Category:1146 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norman Benedictines]]\n[[Category:Abbots of St Albans]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans]]\n[[Category:Burials at St Albans Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=November 2018}}\n'''Geoffrey de Gorham''' (Goreham, [[Gorron]]), sometimes called Geoffrey of Dunstable or of Le Mans (d. at [[St Albans]], 26 February 1146), was a [[Normans|Norman]] scholar who became [[Abbot of St Albans Abbey]], 1119 to 1146.{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Life==\n\nHe was from the [[Maine (province)|province of Maine]], then annexed to the [[Dukedom of Normandy]]. He was invited by Richard d'Aubeney, Abbot of St Albans, to become master of the [[St Albans School (Hertfordshire)|Abbey school]]. On his arrival, he found that owing to his long delay another had been appointed, whereupon he opened a school at [[Dunstable]].{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nHe staged a [[miracle play]] on [[Catherine of Alexandria|St. Katherine]]. A chronicle relates how he had borrowed some [[cope]]s from [[St Albans Cathedral|St Albans Abbey]] for the performance, but had the misfortune to lose his books and the copes in a fire at his house in the night after the performance. To make up to God and the saint for the loss of the copes, he determined to become a monk of St Albans Abbey.<ref>Richard Axton, ''European Drama of the Early Middle Ages'' (1974), p. 161.</ref> \n\nHere he rose to be prior, and finally was elected abbot on the death of Richard, in 1119. He ruled for twenty-six years, and the abbey prospered. He succeeded in saving the Abbey when it was threatened with destruction during [[the Anarchy]] during the reign of King [[Stephen of England|Stephen]].{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nHe added to the building an infirmary with chapel attached, and spent large sums on a new shrine to which he translated the body of [[Saint Alban|St Alban]], 2 August 1129. {{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nGeoffrey endowed the nunnery at [[Sopwell Priory|Sopwell]], and founded another at [[Markyate]], in [[Hertfordshire]], for his friend and counsellor, [[Christina of Markyate]] the [[recluse]]. He also opened a [[leper hospital]] near St Albans.{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==References==\n\n;Attribution\n*{{Catholic|wstitle=Geoffrey of Dunstable}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geoffrey De Gorham}}\n[[Category:1146 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norman Benedictines]]\n[[Category:Abbots of St Albans]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Normans]]\n[[Category:Burials at St Albans Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "name_user": "FeanorStar7", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geoffrey_de_Gorham"}
{"title_page": "Raisen", "text_new": "{{About|the municipality in Madhya Pradesh, India|its namesake district|Raisen District|the dried fruit|Raisin}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Raisen\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Town\n| image_skyline           = Raisen Fort, Madhya Pradesh.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Raisen fort\n| nickname                = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = India Madhya Pradesh#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|23.33|N|77.8|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = India\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Raisen district|Raisen]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = Its historic places.\n| government_type         =\n| leader_title            = MLA\n| leader_name             = Dr. PrabhuRam Chaudhary [[Indian National Council|INC]]\n| leader_title2           = Mayor   \n|leader_name2    =  Jamna Sen  [[BJP]]\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 44162\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code             = \n| registration_plate    = MP-38\n| website                 = {{URL|www.raisen.nic.in}}\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-MP]]\n| footnotes               =  \n}}\n'''Raisen''' is a town and a [[municipality]] in [[Raisen district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Madhya Pradesh]]. It is the administrative headquarters of Raisen District. Raisen takes its name from the massive fort at the top of a hill. The town is located at the foot. The name is probably a corruption of Rajavasini or Rajasayan\u2014the royal residence. The famous places to visit in  [[Raisen district]] are Raisen fort, Dargah, and [[Sanchi|Sanchi Stupa]]. Raisen near 45&nbsp;km from the state Capital [[Bhopal]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe region is predominantly agrarian.\n\n==Tourist Attraction==\nRaisen is mainly known for its ancient age tourist attractions such as Raisen Fort, [[Sanchi Stupa]], [[Bhimbetka]] and [[Bhojpur, Madhya Pradesh|Bhojpur]] town. The city is surrounded by hills and have witnessed a number of tourists visiting the city every year.\n\n=== Raisen Fort ===\nThe Raisen fort is situated at the peek of a hill and has been known for [[Shiva]] temple and [[Mahashivaratri]] celebrations. A working ancient cannon is also placed on the hill which is used during Ramadan for the announcement of sunset.\n\n=== Sanchi Stupa ===\n[[Sanchi Stupa]] is a Buddhist complex and  world heritage situated on the hilltop of Sanchi town. The Stupa was constructed by emperor [[Ashoka]] in [[3rd century BCE]]. A number of tourists (mostly people belonging to [[Buddhist]] community) from various states and countries visits to the Sanchi every year. A museum is also built in the town which has multiple historical items belonging to Stupa.\n\n=== Bhojpur ===\nThe Bhojpur is an ancient and religious town in the Raisen district and one of the most popular tourist attraction in [[Madhya Pradesh]]. The Bhojpur is mainly known for its [[Bhojeshwar Temple]] and Jain Temple. The Bhojeshwar Temple has 18 feet Shivalinga which is known as largest [[Shivalinga]] in the world built in ancient time. A Jain temple is also built near to the Bhojeshwar Temple.\n\n=== Bhimbetka ===\nThe [[Bhimbetka]] rock shelters are an archaeological site in the [[Raisen District]] that spans the prehistoric paleolithic and mesolithic periods, as well as the historic period. It exhibits the earliest traces of human life on the Indian subcontinent and evidence of Stone Age starting at the site in Acheulian times.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Raisen had a population of 35,553. Males constitute 53% of the population and females 47%. Raisen has an average literacy rate of 66%, higher than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 72%, and female literacy is 59%. In Raisen, 15% of the population is under 6 years of age.\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Raisen Fort}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Raisen district}}\n{{Forts in India}}\n{{Forts in Madhya Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Raisen district]]\n[[Category:Raisen| ]]\n[[Category:Forts in Madhya Pradesh|Raisen Fort]]\n\n\n{{MadhyaPradesh-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the municipality in Madhya Pradesh, India|its namesake district|Raisen District|the dried fruit|Raisin}}\n{{more citations needed|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Raisen\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| settlement_type         = Town\n| image_skyline           = Raisen Fort, Madhya Pradesh.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Raisen fort\n| nickname                = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = India Madhya Pradesh#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|23.33|N|77.8|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = India\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Raisen district|Raisen]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = Its historic places.\n| government_type         =\n| leader_title            = MLA\n| leader_name             = Dr. PrabhuRam Chaudhary [[Indian National Council|INC]]\n| leader_title2           = Mayor   \n|leader_name2    =  Jamna Sen  [[BJP]]\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 44162\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code             = \n| registration_plate    = MP-38\n| website                 = {{URL|www.raisen.nic.in}}\n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-MP]]\n| footnotes               =  \n}}\n'''Raisen''' is a town and a [[municipality]] in [[Raisen district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Madhya Pradesh]]. It is the administrative headquarters of Raisen District. Raisen takes its name from the massive fort at the top of a hill. The town is located at the foot. The name is probably a corruption of Rajavasini or Rajasayan\u2014the royal residence. The famous places to visit in  [[Raisen district]] are Raisen fort, Dargah, and [[Sanchi|Sanchi Stupa]]. Raisen near 45&nbsp;km from the state Capital [[Bhopal]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe region is predominantly agrarian.\n\n==Tourist Attraction==\nRaisen is mainly known for its ancient age tourist attractions such as Raisen Fort, [[Sanchi Stupa]], [[Bhimbetka]] and [[Bhojpur, Madhya Pradesh|Bhojpur]] town. The city is surrounded by hills and have witnessed a number of tourists visiting the city every year.\n\n=== Raisen Fort ===\nThe Raisen fort is situated at the peek of a hill and has been known for [[Shiva]] temple and [[Mahashivaratri]] celebrations. A working ancient cannon is also placed on the hill which is used during Ramadan for the announcement of sunset.\n\n=== Sanchi Stupa ===\n[[Sanchi Stupa]] is a Buddhist complex and  world heritage situated on the hilltop of Sanchi town. The Stupa was constructed by emperor [[Ashoka]] in [[3rd century BCE]]. A number of tourists (mostly people belonging to [[Buddhist]] community) from various states and countries visits to the Sanchi every year. A museum is also built in the town which has multiple historical items belonging to Stupa.\n\n=== Bhojpur ===\nThe Bhojpur is an ancient and religious town in the Raisen district and one of the most popular tourist attraction in [[Madhya Pradesh]]. The Bhojpur is mainly known for its [[Bhojeshwar Temple]] and Jain Temple. The Bhojeshwar Temple has 18 feet Shivalinga which is known as largest [[Shivalinga]] in the world built in ancient time. A Jain temple is also built near to the Bhojeshwar Temple.\n\n=== Bhimbetka ===\nThe [[Bhimbetka]] rock shelters are an archaeological site in the [[Raisen District]] that spans the prehistoric paleolithic and mesolithic periods, as well as the historic period. It exhibits the earliest traces of human life on the Indian subcontinent and evidence of Stone Age starting at the site in Acheulian times.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Raisen had a population of 35,553. Males constitute 53% of the population and females 47%. Raisen has an average literacy rate of 66%, higher than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 72%, and female literacy is 59%. In Raisen, 15% of the population is under 6 years of age.\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Raisen Fort}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Raisen district}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Raisen district]]\n[[Category:Raisen| ]]\n[[Category:Forts in Madhya Pradesh|Raisen Fort]]\n\n\n{{MadhyaPradesh-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Premeditated Chaos", "label": "safe", "comment": "+navbox (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raisen"}
{"title_page": "Fisher (musician)", "text_new": "{{About|the Australian music producer|the American band|Fisher (band)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Fisher (geiler boy)\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name       = Paul Fisher\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1986|11|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n| label            = [[Dirtybird Records|Dirtybird]], Catch & Release\n| genre            = [[Tech house]], [[House music|house]]\n| occupation       = Music producer, DJ\n}}\n'''Paul Nicholas Fisher''', known by the stage name '''Fisher''' (stylised as '''FISHER''')<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/au/artist/fisher/1256012920 |title=FISHER on Apple Music |website=Apple Music AU |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> is an Australian music producer. He was nominated for the 2018 [[ARIA Award]] for [[ARIA Award for Best Dance Release|Best Dance Release]] as well as the [[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]] category at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]] for his solo single \"[[Losing It (song)|Losing It]]\".<ref>{{Citation | last = Moran | first = Robert | last2 = Nathanael | first2 = Cooper | author-link = | date = 11 October 2018 | title = Amy Shark leads the 2018 ARIA nominations in another big year for women | periodical = The Age | url = https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/amy-shark-leads-the-2018-aria-nominations-in-another-big-year-for-women-20181011-p5091h.html }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/12/zedd-disclosure-fisher-receive-2019-grammy-nominations-full-list-nominees/|title=Zedd, FISHER, and more secure 2019 Grammy nominations|date=2018-12-07|website=Dancing Astronaut|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Surfing===\nFisher was a pro surfer on the [[World Surf League#WSL sanctioned tours|World Qualifying Series]] before starting a career in music.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/paul-fisher-interview-music-2017 |title=Former pro surfer Paul Fisher on his career move into music |website=Red Bull |date=8 January 2017 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Chatterjee, Uppy}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nFisher was one half of the DJ duo [[Cut Snake (band)|Cut Snake]]. The group was formed with fellow surfer Leigh \"Sedz\" Sedley. The duo started DJing together while traveling on the pro surfing circuit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.laweekly.com/music/cut-snake-turned-from-pro-surfers-to-professional-djs-5261054 |title=Cut Snake turned from pro surfers to professional DJs |work=LA Weekly |author=Purkrabek, Sarah |date=3 December 2014 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFisher later went solo and started releasing house music tracks under the stage name Fisher.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/fisher-new-single-losing-it-coachella-rip-bootleg-stream-shazam/9991298 |title=First Spin: FISHER finally releases his much-bootlegged banger 'Losing It' |work=ABC |date=13 July 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Newstead, Al}}</ref> In June 2017, Fisher released his debut single \"Ya Kidding\", followed by the EP \"Oi Oi\" in November 2017, which includes the tracks \"Stop It\" and \"Ya Didn't\".\n\nIn March 2018, Fisher released \"Crowd Control\". \"Crowd Control\" came in at number 116 in the Triple J Hottest 100 of 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/18/countdown/101-200 |title=Hottest 200, 2018 |website=ABC |date=28 January 2019 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Fisher released \"[[Losing It (song)|Losing It]]\" which reached number one on the [[List of number-one club tracks of 2018 (Australia)|ARIA Club Tracks Chart]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20180821-0000/Issue1486.pdf |title=The ARIA Report: Week Commencing ~ 20 August 2018 ~ Issue #1486 |publisher=ARIA |date=20 August 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> and made the top 50 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot [[Dance/Electronic Songs]], [[Dance/Mix Show Airplay]], and [[Dance Club Songs]], the latter becoming his first number one in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/8473045/billboard-dance-chart-upstarts-ummet-ozcan-x-laurell-fisher-mono-mind |title=Billboard Dance Chart Upstarts: Ummet Ozcan x Laurell, Fisher & Mono Mind |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=30 August 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Murray, Gordon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8491137/fisher-earns-first-dance-chart-no-1-losing-it |title=Chart Beat: Fisher earns first Dance Chart No. 1, Ariana Grande adds Airplay Top 10 |work=Billboard |date=20 December 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Zellner, Xander}}</ref> \"Losing It\" also garnered Fisher his first [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nomination for \"[[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]]\" at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards|2019 Grammys]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/12/zedd-disclosure-fisher-receive-2019-grammy-nominations-full-list-nominees |title=Zedd, FISHER, and more secure 2019 Grammy nominations |work=Dancing Astronaut |date=12 December 2018 |accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref> \"Losing It\" came in at number 2 in the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2018|Triple J Hottest 100 of 2018]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/18 |title=Hottest 100, 2018 |website=ABC |date=27 January 2019 |accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 2019, Fisher released \"[[You Little Beauty]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/fisher-makes-his-return-with-new-banger-you-little-beauty |title=Fisher makes his return with new banger 'You Little Beauty' |website=Music Feeds |date=10 May 2019 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref> which became his second number one on the Dance Club Songs chart. \"You Little Beauty\" came in at number 53 in the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2019|Triple J Hottest 100 of 2019]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/19 |title=Hottest 100, 2019 |website=ABC |date=25 January 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, Fisher released \"Freaks\", the lead single from his [[extended play]] of the same name. The EP was released on 31 March, alongside the second single \u201cWanna Go Dancin\u2019\u201d.\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Freaks''\n|\n* Released: 31 March 2020<ref name=\"Freaks & EP\"/>\n* Label: Catch & Release\n* Format: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=text-align:center;\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Fisher|title=Discography Fisher|website=australian-charts.com|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(FL)]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/search.asp?search=Fisher&cat=s|title=Fisher in Belgium Charts|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref>Peaks in Ireland:\n* \"Losing It\": {{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Fisher|title=Discography Fisher|website=irish-charts.com|accessdate=18 May 2019}}\n* \"You Little Beauty\": {{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ<br/>Hot]]<br/><ref>Peaks on the NZ Hot Singles Chart:\n* \"Losing It\": {{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4579|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=7 January 2019|accessdate=28 March 2020}}\n* \"Freaks\": {{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4838|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=Recorded Music NZ|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}\n* \"Wanna Go Dancin'\": {{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4845|title=NZ Hot Singles Chart|publisher=Recorded Music NZ|date=13 April 2020|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/54099/fisher/|title=Fisher {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Dance Club Songs|US Dance Club Songs]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Fisher/chart-history/dance-club-play-songs|title=Fisher Dance Club Chart history|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| \"Ya Kidding\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/ya-kidding-single/1253403163 |title=Ya Kidding \u2013 Single by FISHER on Apple Music |website=Apple Music AU |date=30 June 2017\n|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"5\" {{N/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Oi Oi\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/oi-oi-single/1300619152 |title=Oi Oi \u2013 Single by FISHER on Apple Music |website=Apple Music AU |date=10 November 2017 |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Crowd Control\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/crowd-control-single/1347912420 |title=Crowd Control \u2013 Single by FISHER on Apple Music |website=Apple Music AU |date=2 March 2018 |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Losing It (song)|Losing It]]\"\n| 35 || 26 || 60 || 17 || 60 || 1\n|\n* ARIA: Platinum<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSinglesAccreds2019.htm |title=ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2019 Singles |publisher=ARIA |date=31 December 2019 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[You Little Beauty]]\"\n| 2019\n| 41 || 1 || 50 || \u2014 || 78 || 1\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Freaks\"<ref name=\"Freaks & EP\">{{cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/fisher-releases-dance-floor-ready-freaks-from-upcoming-ep |title=Fisher releases dance floor-ready \"Freaks\" from upcoming EP |work=Dancing Astronaut |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |author=Pereira, Natalie}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2020\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 12 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Freaks''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Wanna Go Dancin'\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edm.com/music-releases/fisher-wanna-go-dancin |title=FISHER drops 2nd track of ''Freaks'' EP, 'Wanna Go Dancin'' |last=Cameron |first=John |date=3 April 2020 |website=EDM.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412030628/https://edm.com/music-releases/fisher-wanna-go-dancin |archive-date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 25 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:85%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released.\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n===ARIA Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2018|2018]]\n| ''Losing It''\n| [[ARIA Award for Best Dance Release|Best Dance Release]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2019|2019]]\n| ''You Little Beauty''\n| Best Dance Release\n{{end}}\n\n===[[DJ Mag]]azine top 100 DJs===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Position\n! Notes\n! {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2019\n| 63\n| New Entry\n| rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>https://djmag.com/top-100-djs/poll-2019-fisher</ref>\n|}\n\n===Grammy Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| {{grammy|2019}} \n| \"[[Losing_It_(song)|Losing It]]\" \n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]]\n| {{nom}}\n{{table end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://followthefish.tv/ Fisher Music]\n\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Gold Coast, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Australian house musicians]]\n[[Category:Australian surfers]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Australian music producer|the American band|Fisher (band)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Fisher\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name       = Paul Fisher\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1986|11|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n| label            = [[Dirtybird Records|Dirtybird]], Catch & Release\n| genre            = [[Tech house]], [[House music|house]]\n| occupation       = Music producer, DJ\n}}\n'''Paul Nicholas Fisher''', known by the stage name '''Fisher''' (stylised as '''FISHER''')<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/au/artist/fisher/1256012920 |title=FISHER on Apple Music |website=Apple Music AU |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> is an Australian music producer. He was nominated for the 2018 [[ARIA Award]] for [[ARIA Award for Best Dance Release|Best Dance Release]] as well as the [[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]] category at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]] for his solo single \"[[Losing It (song)|Losing It]]\".<ref>{{Citation | last = Moran | first = Robert | last2 = Nathanael | first2 = Cooper | author-link = | date = 11 October 2018 | title = Amy Shark leads the 2018 ARIA nominations in another big year for women | periodical = The Age | url = https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/amy-shark-leads-the-2018-aria-nominations-in-another-big-year-for-women-20181011-p5091h.html }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/12/zedd-disclosure-fisher-receive-2019-grammy-nominations-full-list-nominees/|title=Zedd, FISHER, and more secure 2019 Grammy nominations|date=2018-12-07|website=Dancing Astronaut|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Surfing===\nFisher was a pro surfer on the [[World Surf League#WSL sanctioned tours|World Qualifying Series]] before starting a career in music.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/paul-fisher-interview-music-2017 |title=Former pro surfer Paul Fisher on his career move into music |website=Red Bull |date=8 January 2017 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Chatterjee, Uppy}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nFisher was one half of the DJ duo [[Cut Snake (band)|Cut Snake]]. The group was formed with fellow surfer Leigh \"Sedz\" Sedley. The duo started DJing together while traveling on the pro surfing circuit.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.laweekly.com/music/cut-snake-turned-from-pro-surfers-to-professional-djs-5261054 |title=Cut Snake turned from pro surfers to professional DJs |work=LA Weekly |author=Purkrabek, Sarah |date=3 December 2014 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFisher later went solo and started releasing house music tracks under the stage name Fisher.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/fisher-new-single-losing-it-coachella-rip-bootleg-stream-shazam/9991298 |title=First Spin: FISHER finally releases his much-bootlegged banger 'Losing It' |work=ABC |date=13 July 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Newstead, Al}}</ref> In June 2017, Fisher released his debut single \"Ya Kidding\", followed by the EP \"Oi Oi\" in November 2017, which includes the tracks \"Stop It\" and \"Ya Didn't\".\n\nIn March 2018, Fisher released \"Crowd Control\". \"Crowd Control\" came in at number 116 in the Triple J Hottest 100 of 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/18/countdown/101-200 |title=Hottest 200, 2018 |website=ABC |date=28 January 2019 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Fisher released \"[[Losing It (song)|Losing It]]\" which reached number one on the [[List of number-one club tracks of 2018 (Australia)|ARIA Club Tracks Chart]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20180821-0000/Issue1486.pdf |title=The ARIA Report: Week Commencing ~ 20 August 2018 ~ Issue #1486 |publisher=ARIA |date=20 August 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> and made the top 50 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot [[Dance/Electronic Songs]], [[Dance/Mix Show Airplay]], and [[Dance Club Songs]], the latter becoming his first number one in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/8473045/billboard-dance-chart-upstarts-ummet-ozcan-x-laurell-fisher-mono-mind |title=Billboard Dance Chart Upstarts: Ummet Ozcan x Laurell, Fisher & Mono Mind |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=30 August 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Murray, Gordon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8491137/fisher-earns-first-dance-chart-no-1-losing-it |title=Chart Beat: Fisher earns first Dance Chart No. 1, Ariana Grande adds Airplay Top 10 |work=Billboard |date=20 December 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |author=Zellner, Xander}}</ref> \"Losing It\" also garnered Fisher his first [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nomination for \"[[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]]\" at the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards|2019 Grammys]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/12/zedd-disclosure-fisher-receive-2019-grammy-nominations-full-list-nominees |title=Zedd, FISHER, and more secure 2019 Grammy nominations |work=Dancing Astronaut |date=12 December 2018 |accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref> \"Losing It\" came in at number 2 in the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2018|Triple J Hottest 100 of 2018]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/18 |title=Hottest 100, 2018 |website=ABC |date=27 January 2019 |accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 May 2019, Fisher released \"[[You Little Beauty]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/fisher-makes-his-return-with-new-banger-you-little-beauty |title=Fisher makes his return with new banger 'You Little Beauty' |website=Music Feeds |date=10 May 2019 |accessdate=11 May 2019}}</ref> which became his second number one on the Dance Club Songs chart. \"You Little Beauty\" came in at number 53 in the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2019|Triple J Hottest 100 of 2019]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/19 |title=Hottest 100, 2019 |website=ABC |date=25 January 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, Fisher released \"Freaks\", the lead single from his [[extended play]] of the same name. The EP was released on 31 March, alongside the second single \u201cWanna Go Dancin\u2019\u201d.\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Freaks''\n|\n* Released: 31 March 2020<ref name=\"Freaks & EP\"/>\n* Label: Catch & Release\n* Format: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[streaming media|streaming]]\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=text-align:center;\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Fisher|title=Discography Fisher|website=australian-charts.com|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(FL)]]<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/search.asp?search=Fisher&cat=s|title=Fisher in Belgium Charts|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref>Peaks in Ireland:\n* \"Losing It\": {{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Fisher|title=Discography Fisher|website=irish-charts.com|accessdate=18 May 2019}}\n* \"You Little Beauty\": {{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size: